<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Kiev pays the price of indecision: Chrystia Freeland on the
background to Ukraine's political crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UKRAINE'S parliament reconvenes today to try to resolve the stalemate that
has led to the most dangerous political and economic crisis since it won
independence 18 months ago.
Unless the three-way tug-of-war between the parliament, the prime minister
and the president is quickly resolved, Kiev is unlikely to muster the
political will to cope with Russia's decision to raise prices for fuel to
world levels.
Failure to respond to steeper energy prices with an austere fiscal and
monetary policy and more rapid moves toward the market could push Ukraine
into hyper-inflation and exacerbate the country's painful drop in industrial
output.
The crisis began two weeks ago, when the cabinet of ministers' extraordinary
power to rule the economy by decree ran out. Promising 'sweat and tears',
Prime Minister Leonid Kuchma asked parliament to extend his powers, and give
him control over Ukraine's spendthrift central bank, in order to push
through his stalled programme of market reforms.
Instead of backing Mr Kuchma, as he had been expected to do, President
Leonid Kravchuk made his own bid for power, asking parliament to amend the
constitution and make the president, rather than the prime minister, head of
the cabinet of ministers.
Parliament rejected Mr Kuchma's offer to resign, thus implicitly turning
down Mr Kravchuk's bid to remove the post of prime minister altogether. But
at the same time, the parliament failed to grant Mr Kuchma the additional
powers he was seeking. The result is that parliament writes the laws, the
prime minister is responsible for running the nuts and bolts of the economy
and the president, who has weak decree-making authority, is overall head of
state.
On May 21, after rejecting both the prime minister's and the president's
requests, parliament offered a vivid demonstration of why this patch-work
political structure is ill-equipped to resolve Ukraine's looming economic
crisis. In response to increases in Russian fuel prices, Ukraine has no
alternative but to raise domestic prices.
But fearing a public outcry, parliament refused to vote for a price rise and
asked the prime minister to authorise price increases. Mr Kuchma refused,
insisting that parliament, having denied him extraordinary power over the
economy, faces the consequences of its decision. President Kravchuk dodged
the issue altogether.
The final outcome: parliament voted to raise the average pension and the
minimum wage but took no decision to raise prices.
One possibility when parliament reconvenes today is that Mr Kuchma will make
a second request for extra powers. But Mr Kuchma has neither the will nor
the savvy to outsmart his political opponents.
A more likely option is that Mr Kravchuk will make a second bid for expanded
authority. Opposition politicians fear that Mr Kravchuk, who has promised to
use additional powers to push through market reforms, will do the opposite
if he wins.
The third possibility, that Ukraine's ex-communist dominated parliament will
again reject both the prime minister's and the president's requests, could
be the most dangerous.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>UAZ  Ukraine, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
