<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Labour advantage eludes UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE lower degree of regulation in Britain's labour market has not given the
country any noticeable competitive edge over other European countries,
according to a survey published today by the Institute for Personnel
Management.
It says: 'There seems to be little correlation between legal regulation and
the attraction of and movement towards flexibility.' The study, based on
research from the Price Waterhouse Cranfield Project, found that employers
across western Europe are increasingly introducing temporary and fixed-term
contracts for workers. There has also been an increase in shift or weekend
working, overtime and sub-contracting as companies move away from the 9 am
to 5 pm, five-day week.
Flexible Working Patterns in Europe; Institute of Personnel Management,
based on research from Cranfield School of Management, Cranfield, Bedford
MK43 OAL.
