<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / German managers come out on top
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH managers think they are the best in Europe but this opinion is not
shared by their continental European competitors, according to a survey of
Europe's smaller companies, published today.
German managers and their companies are the most highly regarded by their
European competitors, though they are modest about their own achievements,
the survey showed. Researchers from Cranfield School of Management
questioned - on behalf of 3i, Britain's largest venture capital company -
just over 1,000 managers of companies employing up to 500 people.
Italian, British and Spanish managers think more highly of themselves than
does the rest of Europe, with the British convinced they are the best.
In the overall European ranking, French managers and their companies were
rated most highly, after the Germans, then the British, the Italians and,
last, the Spanish.
European managers were asked to rank themselves and their foreign
competitors on 12 characteristics. These included competence, reliability,
trustworthiness, humour, and ability to get on with others. Companies were
assessed on aspects such as market and product focus, customer service,
financial viability, and attention to law and ethics.
The researchers then compared how managers rated themselves and their
companies with how they were rated by foreign managers. The difference
between the two represents a measure of the prejudice with which nations
view others, the study said. The biggest discrepancy was between the way the
Italians viewed themselves and the opinion of foreign managers, but they
were closely followed by the British.
British managers were given poor ratings for efficiency, hard work and their
ability to get on with others. The Germans had a modest view of their
strengths and a realistic view of their weaknesses. The French were
considered to be competent but lacking in humour.
The lessons to be drawn from the survey were that companies must communicate
very carefully with overseas customers to overcome the attitudes uncovered.
The Euro-Manager Survey Number 6; 3i/Cranfield European Enterprise Centre,
Cranfield School of Management, Cranfield, Bedford MK43 0AL; tel/fax 0234
751122; no charge.
</TEXT>
