<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Stock exchange urged to shorten settlement period
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LONDON Stock Exchange should abolish its traditional account period and
move quickly to settling share trades on a rolling basis, a Bank of England
sponsored committee is planning to recommend.
Initially, the exchange may move to settling share bargains 10 days after
they are struck, but that might shorten quickly to seven days, then five,
the committee believes.
The committee, headed by Mr Pen Kent, associate director at the Bank of
England, was formed after the collapse in March of the stock exchange's
proposed Taurus paperless settlement system.
The taskforce has been asked to find a 'quick and cheap' solution to
modernising London's cumbersome settlements system and report to the Bank by
the end of June. Under the account system, all share transactions that take
place over a two-week period are settled on a single day a week later. The
committee is said to have asked the stock exchange to review how to adapt
its Talisman settlements system to rolling settlement. A full move to
rolling settlement is unlikely for 12 months. Once that is in place, though,
the committee will recommend that settlement periods rapidly be brought
down.
Also, the committee is said to be considering whether shortening the
settlement period would require London to establish a central depository for
share certificates similar to those used in other leading markets.
Committee members are said to have examined the German Kassenverein, the
US's Depository Trust Company and the Euroclear system used to settle
international bond transactions, and decided that none meets London's needs
sufficiently.
The committee is studying commercial clearing and settlements systems, such
as those provided by Reuters or Thomson Financial Services, to see whether
those 'off-the-peg' systems could be adapted. 'The problem is that none of
these has a built-in custodial and central registrar capacity,' one
committee member said.
Lloyds Bank, the UK's largest central registrar of share certificates, is
said to have proposed itself as the supplier of a registration system to
interact with any commercial system selected.
Meanwhile, there are signs that trying to satisfy competing commercial
interests of City firms remains a stumbling block. Committee members have
agreed that the interests of users, rather than of service providers such as
registrars, should prevail. However, marketmakers - firms which agree to buy
and sell shares in specific companies under all conditions - are said to be
displeased that the settlements period is not contracting more quickly.
Private client stockbrokers, who are also represented on the committee, are
said to be unhappy about plans to contract the settlement period much
further.
Stock exchange probe, Page 22
Shorter bond settlement, Page 25
See Lex
</TEXT>
