<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Move to speed London SE trade settlement is likely
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LONDON Stock Exchange should abolish its traditional account period and
move quickly to settling share trades on a rolling basis, a Bank of England
sponsored committee is planning to recommend.
Initially, the exchange may move to settling share bargains 10 days after
they are struck, but that might shorten quickly to seven days, then five,
the committee believes.
The committee, headed by Mr Pen Kent, associate director at the Bank of
England, was formed after the collapse in March of the stock exchange's
proposed Taurus paperless settlement system.
The taskforce has been asked to find a 'quick and cheap' solution to
modernising London's cumbersome settlements system and to report to the Bank
of England by the end of June. Under the account system, all share
transactions that take place over a two-week period are settled on a single
day a week later.
The committee is said to have asked the stock exchange to review how to
adapt its Talisman settlements system to rolling settlement.
A full move to rolling settlement is unlikely for 12 months. Once that is in
place, though, the committee will recommend that settlement periods rapidly
be brought down.
Also, the committee is said to be considering whether shortening the
settlement period would require London to establish a central depository for
share certificates similar to those used in other leading markets.
Committee members are said to have examined the German Kassenverein, the
US's Depository Trust Company and the Euroclear system used to settle
international bond transactions, and decided that none meets London's needs
sufficiently.
The committee is studying commercial clearing and settlements systems, such
as provided by Reuters or Thomson Financial Services, to see whether those
'off-the-peg' systems could be adapted. 'The problem is that none of these
has a built-in custodial and central registrar capacity,' one committee
member said.
Lloyds Bank, the UK's largest central registrar of share certificates, is
said to have proposed itself as the supplier of a registration system to
interact with any commercial system selected by the committee.
Meanwhile, there are signs that trying to satisfy the competing commercial
interests of City firms remains a stumbling block. Committee members have
agreed that the interests of users, rather than of service providers such as
registrars, should prevail.
However, market makers - those firms which agree to buy and sell shares in
specific companies under all conditions - are said to be displeased that the
settlements period is not contracting more quickly.
Meanwhile, private client stockbrokers, who are also represented on the
committee, are said to be unhappy about plans to contract the settlement
period much further. Private client stockbrokers cannot collect funds from
their customers quickly enough to settle bargains five days after they are
struck.
