<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Personal View: Why the chancellor must act tough
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RUPERT DARWALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
During the last election, Mr John Major said Britain had never been in a
better position to borrow. Even if it was true then, it is no longer the
case. Although the budget Red Book, projects a run of large but declining
PSBRs, these all represent additions to the existing stock of debt. With
nominal interest rates some two points higher than the growth of nominal
GDP, debt service costs will rise, as a proportion of GDP, with debt
interest costs tending to rise exponentially.
This means the costs of stabilising the debt to GDP ratio rise with each
passing year. Last year debt interest cost Pounds 17.5bn and is projected to
rise to Pounds 29bn in 1997-98. Stabilisation of the debt ratio requires a
primary surplus - that is before debt interest - sufficient to pay the real
interest on the debt. On current plans, this would require a fiscal
adjustment in four years' time roughly equivalent to raising the basic rate
of income tax from 25 per cent to 30 per cent.
Rising debt service costs have an impact on public spending and the control
of inflation. The growth of debt servicing costs puts pressure on other
spending programmes, which have been growing very rapidly. Over the last
three years, public spending rose by 13 per cent in real terms whilst the
economy contracted. It is sometimes forgotten that public spending is a cost
on the wealth creating part of the economy, funded by taxes and borrowing,
which is deferred taxation. Sooner or later increased taxes are passed
through in the form of higher costs, reducing competitiveness. A case is
made that capital spending, particularly on infrastructure, is different as
it yields a return. But in the best cases, the returns are low, albeit long
term.
Cutting public spending is difficult, particularly if so much is ring fenced
by the manifesto, a document which is becoming the most expensive suicide
note in political history. As the case of Belgium or Italy shows, it is easy
to run up debt, but difficult to reduce it and requires high tax rates to
service it. The risk is that the fiscal options will have been closed off
for a decade, during which time the main task of fiscal policy will be an
unremitting effort to turn the deficit into a primary surplus.
An increasing national debt also makes the operation of monetary policy and
the control of inflation more difficult. Unlike in the 1970s, inflation will
not erode the real value of debt significantly without the re-imposition of
exchange controls. If inflationary worries resurface, bondholders would
switch their holdings to investments where they can maintain positive real
returns. As a result, nominal gilt yields will rise. It is thus vital for
the government that inflationary expectations remain low. So far the rise in
debt service costs has been partially offset by falling yields. But this
could be quickly reversed.
With a current account deficit as well as the large fiscal deficit, there is
a risk that investors will become nervous about the UK economy returning to
a sustainable balance within a realistic period. Such fears could lead to a
run on sterling, placing the government in an awkward position - to raise
interest rates to offset the loosening in monetary policy, so putting the
recovery at risk, or instead letting sterling fall, boosting nominal
competitiveness but risking any inflationary consequences. Political
weakness at such a time would increase the likelihood of a wrong choice.
The UK's political culture makes it extraordinarily difficult to have a
sensible debate on these central issues. Two weeks ago, Michael Portillo
made a speech reviewing the issues and stating his preference for action on
public spending. What unfolded was a typical Whitehall story; a leak about
prescription charges, probably from the Department of Health, made the
speech headline news and the media were off to hunt-the-manifesto-pledge.
Too often economic issues are written about in a narrow tactical context
such as the relative power of one minister against another.
This is very different from Germany, facing its own fiscal crisis caused by
unification. There the debate is being conducted in terms of growth versus
distribution - spending cuts versus tax increases. In the UK we have not got
to first base. In this respect, one of the world's oldest democracies has
some growing up to do. Mr Clarke's appointment as Chancellor might help to
change this. If he confronts the fiscal deficit and explains the options,
his authority would be enhanced, as happened to Paul Keating, who, as
Australian finance minister in 1987 took tough measures to cut the deficit.
If, and only if, Mr Clarke can cut public spending as ruthlessly will he be
well placed to earn the leadership of his party.
The author is former special adviser to Norman Lamont and an investment
banker
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
