<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Leading Article: Mr Major's next steps
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE signs are that Mr John Major's re-shuffle of his Cabinet has failed to
free him from factional strife inside his party. There is talk that the
prime minister may well face a leadership challenge in the course of 1994.
Given the wounds of the Newbury by-election and the likelihood that
Christchurch will inflict a further gash, there is cause for prime
ministerial anxiety. Perhaps there is no escape from this dizzying descent
into political ineffectiveness. Mr Major, a man of unsure political
identity, was chosen because his colleagues wanted no more of Mrs Thatcher,
but did not know what they wanted instead. Normally, parties in identity
crisis recuperate in opposition. That the Conservatives are not doing so is
a fearsome indictment of the Labour party.
The continuing feebleness of the opposition is one of several reasons why Mr
Major need not feel entirely gloomy. Bigger ones are the economic recovery
and fact that parliamentary warfare over Maastricht is as good as over. Last
week's timid re-shuffle might yet add a fourth, if the new team can help
define a post-Thatcher conservative project to unite all but the most
embittered Europhobes inside the party.
In his interview with the FT last week, Mr Major displayed his strengths and
his weakness. His strong points include a doggedness of purpose and personal
charm, once considered a decisive electoral asset. He has also dealt with
the debris Mrs Thatcher left behind: the poll tax, soaring inflation,
recession and chaos inside her own party on Europe. Even his responsibility
for Britain's unedifying tangle with the exchange rate mechanism of the
European monetary system cannot obscure the achievement. Of the weaknesses,
one, the slimness of Mr Major's majority in the House of Commons, is without
remedy. A second, the government's reputation for competence, is closely
linked to the first; a government which speaks loudly and carries a small
stick is apt to look foolish. On coal, education and penal policy, Mr Major
and his ministers have appeared by turns vainglorious, penitent and
incompetent. Even last week, recrimination surrounded the launch of policies
for transport and science, suggesting a government which might have
difficulty organising a sing-song at a Welsh drinking party. If he cannot
run a competent government, Mr Major will not deserve to go on governing.
The vision thing
But there is a third weakness which lies at the heart of his difficulties.
In the interview, he was asked where, in a Cabinet of consolidators on one
side and radicals on the other, he stands himself. In rejecting such labels,
he said: 'When I see something that I believe is wrong, I will want to
change it. Where I see something that operates broadly with the grain of the
British instinct, I won't want to change it.'
As an appeal to a national temperament which dislikes ideologues, this is
fine, but it is not the basis for a political platform, on which others can
build; it lacks, in President Bush's words, the vision thing. A prime
minister has to be able to set out the political principles against which
choices must be made. If he cannot, those who wish to support him will lack
a framework for so doing, and his opponents will see him as so much chaff.
What might a new Conservative vision involve and how could it bear on the
two great questions in British politics: the economy and Europe? Here is a
suggestion: the government will seek to return as much power as possible to
its citizens.
It can do so in a number of ways: by restraining the level of taxation, so
that individuals have maximum discretion over spending; by giving the public
more information, better right of redress and effective, open and
accountable government at the local, national and European level. In other
words, Mr Major would turn the tide on the centralised state which Mrs
Thatcher used to attack deep ills. He would do so while building on the
foundations of Thatcherism - a liberal, open economy exposed to the maximum
competitive pressure; a corporate sector freed from excessive taxation and
damagingly powerful trade unions; a commitment to low inflation and prudent
public finances, including a determination to contain the public sector at
around 40 per cent of GDP. This year, driven partly by the recession, the
figure will exceed 45.5 per cent, at a time when revenues represent only 37
per cent of GDP.
Timorous step
It is clear that Mr Major is instinctively attracted by much of this, but
his actions, such as the citizen's charter, have been inadequate. He heads a
government machine which prefers governing in the dark, where Whitehall
knows best and the Treasury knows best of all; never mind that this gave
Britain the poll tax, boom and bust, the ERM, the pits debacle and the
confrontation over school tests.
It is not true that nothing can be done. The panel of advisers at the
Treasury is a timorous step in the right direction, but what the UK really
needs is an independent central bank, accountable for achieving a specific
inflation target, and a council of economic advisers capable of carrying
independent weight in the pay-setting debate.
Whether or not the Bank of England is made independent, fiscal policy has to
be tightened. If not, an appreciating exchange rate may again be used as the
main instrument for securing low inflation, thus again tending to
destabilise incentives for the production of tradeable goods and services.
This implies a firm attack on public expenditure, which in turn calls for
the political boldness to target benefits on those who most need them,
rather than re-cycling middle-classes taxes as middle-class subsidies. Where
services are efficiently provided by public-sector agencies, individuals who
can afford to should be asked to pay, and they should be able to pay
directly for a premium level of service. Obvious targets are subsidised
home-ownership and free higher education for all, but the scale of the
financial problem demands that the principle also be applied in social
security, pensions and the health service.
There is a connection between public finances and better governance. In the
first place, big changes to the welfare state require consent, and consent
requires debate. Also, the excellent principle of the purchaser-provider
splits in public services demands more effective mechanisms to develop
competition among providers and to make the purchasers (for example, health
authorities) accountable. Whitehall cannot be the sole conduit for this
process, nor can Whitehall's ugly quango offspring. A start must also be
made in restoring fiscal autonomy to local authorities, which today depend
upon central government grants for 85 per cent of their income.
Poor watchdogs
Pluralism in governance is healthy because it places power and
responsibility at the right level and because it encourages diversity. The
government recognises this in the EC context, where Mr Major wants the
community to take a hard and realistic look at the role of the commission,
the European Parliament and the council of ministers which, jointly and
severally, fall well short of acceptable standards of openness and
accountability. This debate, however, cannot avoid examining the role of
national parliaments, which have been poor watchdogs of the EC thus far;
perhaps Britain's House of Lords could be made democratic and given such a
role.
Here then, is an agenda for Mr Major. In it, he champions individual
responsibility and opportunity and attacks monopoly power and overmighty
institutions. He constrains the state, but makes it more democratic, more
economically productive. Perhaps he even unites his party and looks like a
winner again.
</TEXT>
