<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Observer: Finding out Who's Who
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Is nothing sacred? When a pillar of the establishment, like Lord Erroll of
Hale, attacks Who's Who, the 145-year-old dictionary of people who are
thought to matter in Britain, then the prime minister's vision of a
classless society may not be as far away as sometimes imagined.
Lord Erroll, who was president of the Board of Trade when Harold Macmillan
was running the country in the early 1960s, accuses the 2,000 page reference
book of being 'too fat and too heavy' and says that he has no idea of how
people are selected for inclusion. Hear, hear.
In a letter to The Times yesterday, he says that the self-important tome
needs stricter editorial control, citing the example of romantic novelist
Dame Barbara Cartland who has a 200 line entry all to herself, whilst former
US president Ronald Reagan merits just 12 lines. There are plenty of other
examples of the quirkiness of a reference book which is regarded by many as
the establishment bible. The late Robert Maxwell, for instance, had a 50
line entry whereas Sir Owen Green of BTR has just seven lines. Lord King's
entry is more than twice as long as that of his heroine - Lady Thatcher.
Lord Erroll (25 lines) is not the first to sound a rebellious note. The
Economist, the FT's sister publication, once described Who's Who as
Britain's second-most-secret institution noting that its name is not even
listed in the telephone directory.
Surely, now that Stella Rimington has been named as boss of MI5, the country
can be permitted to know who chairs the Who's Who selection board?
</TEXT>
