<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Letter: Contrary positions on energy expectations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ANDREW WARREN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The announcement by the World Bank at the Financial Times' Asian
Electricity conference ('Asia energy needs double', May 25) that it expects
Asia's energy consumption to double during this decade - with Dollars 500bn
being spent on new power generating capacity - coincides with your 'Power
Generation Equipment' supplement of May 25.
That supplement predicted a positive orgy for the power plant construction
industry, forecasting vast increases in construction around the world. To
quote at random: 'Power capacity additions in Asia are running at triple the
rate seen in the 1970s. China and Hong Kong will be adding 12-15 GW of new
power capacity every year for the rest of this decade - the equivalent of
Switzerland's entire installed power capacity.'
It is now precisely one year since the leaders of 150 nations gathered in
Rio for the Earth Summit. Each leader solemnly signed a commitment to seek
to stabilise the earth's climate, by ensuring a reduction in the amount of
carbon dioxide emitted into the atmosphere from energy consumption. Many of
those leaders came from precisely the same countries where such enormous
growth in energy demand is now being forecast so blithely.
It is not entirely clear to me how it is possible to endorse both positions.
Perhaps someone at the World Bank might care to try?
Andrew Warren,
director,
Association for the
Conservation of Energy,
9 Sherlock Mews,
London W1M 3RH
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XOZ  Asia.
</CN>
