<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Letter: Priority in former Yugoslavia is to impose sanctions
on Croatia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr CHARLES JENKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Much commentary on Bosnia-Hercegovina and the former Yugoslavia focuses
on mistakes that may have been made in the past. There is little point in
this. However, there is a lot of point in trying to avoid mistakes in the
future.
At present there are two priorities. The most immediate one should be the
imposition of sanctions on Croatia. The behaviour of the single party
Croatian Democratic Union (HDZ) regime towards Bosnia-Hercegovina is, at the
present juncture, notably worse than that of the Socialist Party Serbian
regime, in that: (a) the aggression of the Herceg-Bosnian authorities
towards the Moslems is directed by the local branch of the HDZ, which is
organically linked to Zagreb; Mr Karadzic's Serbian Democratic Party is not
so linked to the Serbian Socialist Party; (b) the Serbian regime is at least
apparently making an effort to impose sanctions on the Bosnian Serbs.
This is not to suggest that there is any room to let up on sanctions on
Belgrade before it has genuinely isolated the Bosnian Serbs, but
international policy must be consistent and even-handed if it is to earn
respect. Moreover, most Moslems have already been ethnically cleansed from
Serb occupied areas, while on the contrary the Croat controlled areas, and
Croatia itself, include hundreds of thousands of Moslem refugees. Croatia's
collusion in the aggression and the cynical misinterpretation of the
Vance-Owen plan by the Croat Hercegovinans thus puts hundreds of thousands
of lives at risk. The West may feel that it has to work with Croatia to help
it cope with its refugees, but if they are not safe in Croatia, they will
inevitably escape in ever larger numbers, however unwelcome they are made to
feel. Even the most narrow and mean-minded western self interest would thus
justify a tougher stance towards Croatia.
Croatia is more susceptible than Serbia to being made an international
pariah, because its catholicism makes it feel that it should be a part of
western Europe. However, it is all too clear that the Croatian regime does
not react to diplomatic pressure on its own, if not backed up by the kind of
sanctions which would make it clear that Croat behaviour is unacceptable. If
sanctions are not imposed now, Croatia may allow itself to be dragged too
far into a deal to carve up Bosnia-Hercegovina with the Bosnian Serbs, ever
to be able to extricate itself.
The second priority is to reinforce existing UN forces in protecting safe
havens, to extend them to Moslem populations in Herceg-Bosnia, and to make
it clear that air attacks will be launched on any artillery endangering the
civilians and UN troops in the safe havens.
Charles Jenkins,
9 Leppoc Road,
London SW4 9LS.
</TEXT>
