<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Arts: Romeo and Juliet - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MALCOLM RUTHERFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The posters are obscurely proclaiming Juliet 4 Romeo, and there are some
ominous programme notes about the role of women. Do not be perturbed,
however; the English Shakespeare Company's Romeo and Juliet, sponsored by
IBM, turns out to be full of fun, not at all distorted and owes nothing to
West Side Story. It is one of the most enjoyable that I have seen. Freshness
abounds.
Michael Bognadov's direction works by an accumulation of small touches. For
examples, Julia Dearden's Nurse is young, attractive and very noticeably
Irish, which adds a playful element to a part sometimes played by a woman
too old. John Dougall's Mercutio is slightly Scottish with a fondness for
the national drink as well as the Italian wine. Friar John, who has barely a
couple of lines, seems to be Welsh.
Christopher Saul's Friar Lawrence is firmly Oxford English, but also young.
He rides an old-fashioned black lady's bicycle with a carrier basket in
front and oils the chain himself. The only villain in the piece is Colin
Farrell's Capulet whose English is pronouncedly north country and who thinks
he can tell his daughter what to do.
Peter Theiss's Tybalt is a tall, swaggering figure in purple trousers; the
novelty is that he has a blonde at his side to show off to - she smokes his
cheroot while he is handling his sword.
Such innovations continue. The fight scene is a wonderful mixture of
umbrellas, swords, punches and kicks, with a pause for a drink, but nothing
shocking. When Juliet wants to prevent Romeo from leaving at dawn, she hides
one of his boots under the pillow so that he has to touch her to retrieve
it. There is an unobtrusive media presence on the morning that Paris is
supposed to claim his bride. And when the Montagues and the Capulets are
finally reconciled, a press photographer quietly takes pictures.
The production is very simple. The ball scene is not spectacular, nor the
tomb scene at the end. Bognadov dispenses with the traditional balcony and
merely has Romeo on a perfectly safe pair of ladders while Juliet stands on
a table.
Unusually for our times, the sexual attraction between the lovers is not
explicitly played up. They embrace, of course, but their rapport could be
just as much cerebral as physical.
Capulet is the odd man out. Not only does he sound as if he made money out
of the industrial revolution; he is a bully and is none too gracious to his
wife, let alone Juliet. Yet even he joins in the remorse at the end.
For this is a production about basically nice people. There is not much
passion, but there is a lot of entertainment. The use of the torches in a
darkened theatre at the finish as the families of descend into the tomb is a
flash of theatrical brilliance. Equally clever is is the dropping of much of
the final scene where Friar Lawrence explains what has happened to an
audience that already knows.
Joe Dixon's Romeo and Joanna Roth's Juliet will go down as quiet lovers.
They have the compensation of knowing that they are part of a production
that provides great pleasure and does not overdo the melodrama. Maybe
playing up the fun is the right way to do it.
Lyric Theatre, Hammersmith until June 19. (081) 741 2311
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7922 Theatrical Producers and Services.
</IN>
