<PROFILE>_AN-DFBBWAGAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930601
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Arts: Balanchine celebrated - Clement Crisp hails the New
York City Ballet season
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLEMENT CRISP
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
George Balanchine died in April 1983. Ten years on, his New York City Ballet
is mounting a Balanchine Celebration which will show no less than 73 of his
creations in an eight-week season. The scale of the enterprise, no less than
the importance of the ballets on view, is tremendous. Many of these works
are the bed-rock of the company; a few - because Balanchine replaced or
discarded pieces without qualm - have been rescued from the memories of
early casts after the passage of years. Balanchine's oeuvre consisted of
more than 400 dance-works; this season is both a retrospective and an
affirmation of identity by his heirs.
A decision was made that the festival's repertory should be shown
chronologically. The effect is stimulating. The ballets may be viewed as a
chain of artistic experience (and marvellous craftsmanship) which links past
and present. The range, the vitality, the unfailing felicity of Balanchine's
output - genius as technical expertise; inspiration as practicality - can
still take one's breath away, and at every performance still do. In six
performances during four days I saw 16 works made between 1946 and 1955. In
them Balanchine did everything with steps, from clothing music in plotless
dance (Concerto Barocco) to telling stories (La Sonnambula); from tickling
the palate with the happiest bravura (Minkus pas de trois) to evoking the
darkly numinous in Ivesiana and reshaping myth in Orpheus. In his recension
of Swan Lake he renewed the past; in Four Temperaments he made the classic
dance new for our time. And in everything he hymned the power of classicism
to ennoble human ability.
The significance of this season for the New York public is clear. As with
the recent Matisse show, they are given an illuminating survey of a great
master's work. Balanchine is unassailably the dominant choreographer of this
century. His working life in America - an exact half-century - made classic
ballet an American art, and he gave the danse d'ecole its truest and most
influential form for our time, developed logically from the Imperial Russian
traditions in which he had been reared. Marius Petipa's career in St.
Petersburg was the culmination and summation of 19th century ballet.
Balanchine's work in New York is a no less grand and definitive achievement
for us. Invited to America in 1933 by Lincoln Kirstein, and sustained in
everything thereafter by Kirstein's massive gifts and his determination that
classic ballet should have an American identity, Balanchine naturalised the
academic dance through a school, a company, and a repertory that dominates
the history of ballet.
And Balanchine still astonishes us - not just by the power of his genius,
but with the prodigality and ease of his inventiveness. (Like Saint-Saens,
he created without apparent effort - 'as easily as an apple-tree produces
apples'). A former member of his company told me how, in two months during
the winter of 1957/8, Balanchine was working on four ballets at the same
time, moving from studio to studio during the day, choreographing Agon (a
masterpiece of ballet in our century), Square Dance, Gounod Symphony and
Stars and Stripes, works as different in manner as they are in score (from
Stravinsky to Sousa, by way of Gounod, Vivaldi and Corelli). All are still
in performance.
The 16 ballets I saw showed Balanchine at the time he was building a
repertory to sustain his dancers and his audience as his company acquired a
permanent home at the City Centre in 1948. There were two happy
restorations. Bourree Fantasque is a loving response to Chabrier music, apt
in wit as in sentiment, and it was marvellously danced by Darci Kistler and
Damian Woetzel, Kyra Nichols and Erlends Zieminch. Haieff Divertimento
(named for its composer, Alexei Haieff) was a delicate piece that was long
thought lost. Carefully re-studied, it returns to the stage as a touching
view of youthful emotion, and is as gently delightful as it was in 1950 when
NYCB brought it to London on the company's first and memorably exciting
visit.
Major works - Concerto Barocco, Scotch Symphony, Ivesiana, Western Symphony,
the second act of Nutcracker - were well done, while Four Temperaments
remains, after 46 years, a work so prescient, so bold, that it is still
vastly more modern than the European flash-dance of today. Certain ballets
were unwisely cast. Orpheus lacked any focus because of the inexperience of
Nilas Martins in its title role; La Sonnambula and La Valse suffered from
unsuitable central performance, though in the former, Peter Boal caught
exactly the sudden fever of emotion that will destroy its poet hero.
A group of delicious small pieces - Balanchine's lollipops - were fetchingly
done. The Minkus pas de trois (the old trio from Paquita which Balanchine
made more difficult, pour encourager les autres) found Damian Woetzel happy
to dazzle us with diamond-cut beats and turns. The Sylvia pas de deux, the
iridescent Valse Fantaisie, its dancers skimming like dragonflies, looked as
delightful as ever. There were, though, two artists who dominated these
performances: Kyra Nichols and Darci Kistler. Kistler's stage identity is
youthfully radiant, grand. In Nutcracker she produced lustrous dancing,
touched with majesty. In Swan Lake her Odette was superb in scale; in
Concerto Barocco she inhabited the music, while in Bourree Fantasque's first
movement she and Damian Woetzel flirted wittily with the dance and with each
other.
Kyra Nichols is a classic ballerina of rarest distinction. She dances with
an absolute ease, entire denial of self, a musicality and an authority that
seem wholly natural and wholly convincing. Her roles acquire thereby a
simplicity that seems inevitable. Her style is generous, choreographic
beauty revealed through a dedication to the movement itself. Watching her,
you wonder why other ballerinas cannot be as true; and you know that Kyra
Nichols' genius lies in just this miraculous truth. Magisterial her art
certainly is, but also innocent, because so pure. She danced Scotch Symphony
with such sweetness, and such gentle dignity, that I longed to see her as
Bournonville's sylphide. In Swan Lake, which is Balanchine's fantasy on
themes by Ivanov, her account of Odette was marvellous in its grandeur of
scale as in its tragic dignity. And I do not know another dancer today whose
pas de bourree - that cascade of little steps that the old ballerinas said
should look like a string of perfectly matched pearls - is so exquisite or
so expressive.
From the company there came dancing strong, assured, and, for the most part,
exhilarating in dynamics as in sense of purpose. This celebration is very
important: through it, New York City Ballet examines and re-affirms its
glorious Balanchinian identity. And we rejoice.
The Balanchine Celebration continues at the State Theatre, New York, until
June 27. Leading benefactors are the Lila Acheson and DeWitt Wallace Fund
for Lincoln Center, and The Brown Foundation Inc
</TEXT>
