<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Occasionally a programme catches the public imagination even before it goes
out, and interest balloons in a disproportionate way. Often the subject is
connected, albeit remotely, with sex as is the case today with Giving The
Empire A Lift.
This half-hour programme on ITV (7.30pm) depicts a typical day at Rigby &amp;
Peller, the London corsetiere which makes brassieres for the Queen among
others. We are promised the confessions and fetishes of the company's
clients and a first-time fitting for a woman who discovers that, for years,
like many others, she has been buying bras that don't really fit.
Before that in BBC1's sequence of repeats, Wildlife 100 at 7pm shows the
memorable programme 'Twentieth Century Fox' which, in 1981 when most of us
were unaware of such things, showed the habits of urban foxes. Assignment
(7.45pm BBC 2) explores 'The Galician Connection': the route now taken by
Colombia's cocaine producers to ship drugs in to Europe via Galicia in
north-west Spain.
