<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Cambodia poll row raises tension: Khmer Rouge guerrillas
renew killings amid election wrangling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PHNOM PENH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TENSION increased in Cambodia yesterday, after the government urged the
United Nations to stop announcing results of last week's election because of
'irregularities' and after Khmer Rouge guerrillas attacked UN forces.
With nearly half the ballot papers counted, the communist government's
Cambodian People's Party and Funcinpec, the royalist opposition party, each
had about 40 per cent of the vote, according to the UN Transitional
Authority in Cambodia (Untac).
A balance between the CPP and Funcinpec is regarded as an ideal outcome by
most countries behind the 1991 Paris peace accord, which paved the way for
the UN-organised election.
Neither would be able to dictate the constitution because it must be
approved by a two-thirds majority in the new 120-member assembly, and the
two parties might even have to form a coalition government after the
constitution is set up. 'Cambodians have voted for national reconciliation,'
said a European diplomat.
But the CPP is unhappy about its failure to make a stronger showing in the
election. Mr Sok An, CPP spokesman, announced that the party and the
government had asked Untac to postpone the proclamation of results - to
which many Cambodians are listening avidly on Untac radio.
Mr Sok An and another government official who raised the matter yesterday
with Mr Reginald Austin, Untac election chief, were said by one Untac
official to be looking 'very worried and jumpy'. Mr Sok An said there had
been a number of irregularities, including Untac polling officers trying to
influence voting and reports of broken ballot-box seals.
Some seals have been broken in transit on Cambodia's rough roads, but Untac
insists no one has interfered with the ballot-boxes. Untac last night
rejected the CPP's request and said the announcement of results would
continue.
Khmer Rouge guerrillas, who signed and then rejected the 1991 peace accord
and made vain attempts to dissuade Cambodians from voting, appear to be
stepping up their military operations, Untac officials say.
A Uruguayan UN soldier was killed and three Uruguayan and Polish
peacekeepers were injured yesterday when suspected Khmer Rouge gunmen
ambushed two Untac vehicles in Kompong Cham province.
On Sunday night, 60 Khmer Rouge guerrillas attacked and ransacked a market
in Kampot province and twice directed their fire at a French UN military
position, Untac said. Two Cambodians were reported killed. Both the French
in Kampot and the ambushed peackeepers in Kompong Cham fired back at their
attackers.
Untac announced at the weekend that Bangladeshi UN positions in northern
Cambodia had been shelled and that four civilians had been killed in Kampot
province in a grenade attack directed at ethnic Vietnamese playing cards in
a marketplace.
UN forces are due to remain in Cambodia for another three months. By then a
new government should be in place. In the meantime, Untac is on the alert
and its armoured cars patrol the streets of Phnom Penh at night.
A philosophical Mr Yasushi Akashi, head of Untac, responded to a question
about the future by quoting Mr Yogi Berra, the US baseball great. 'It ain't
over till it's over,' he said.
</TEXT>
