<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Smartest policy for Republicans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Clinton administration is going through a rough patch. But Republicans
are naive if they expect an easy presidential victory in 1996. The business
cycle favours the Democrats. So does the fall of communism, which has
removed an external threat that once served to unite right-wingers. Worse,
after the drift of the Bush years, the conservative movement lacks
definition. Instead of presenting a clear alternative to Clintonism, a
jumble of factions - ranging from born-again Christians to patrician
traditionalists and crypto-protectionists - are vying for influence.
If conservatives are to win political power, in the legislative as well as
executive branch, they need a new unifying vision. Yet after the political
gyrations of recent decades, it might seem that every possible 'ism' has
been tried, usually with disappointing results. In fact, there is one
philosophy that has never been consistently advocated - classical
19th-century liberalism. For some reason, politicians who advocate
laissez-faire economic policies usually favour conservative social policies.
Social liberals, on the other hand, nearly always advocate interventionist
economic policies.
The pattern is perfectly illustrated by Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton.
President Reagan cut taxes and deregulated the economy but tightened
anti-abortion laws. President Clinton fights for gay rights yet wants to
raise tax rates and increase government intervention in the economy. There
is no mileage in Republicans attempting to outflank Democrats as economic
regulators. But suppose they favoured freedom in all spheres, social as well
as economic? Might this not be a winning combination?
A book* edited by Mr David Boaz and Mr Edward Crane of the Cato Institute, a
Washington think-tank, makes a strong case for precisely this combination of
policies. Cato scholars are usually regarded as card-carrying conservatives.
But Boaz and Crane chaff at the label, on the grounds that they are keener
on radical reform than almost anybody else, certainly than Democrats. They
would call themselves 'liberals', had American left-wingers not expropriated
that title. Since 'classical liberal' sounds rather backward-looking, they
have settled on 'market liberal' as shorthand for their political
philosophy.
'Market liberals have a cosmopolitan, inclusive vision for society. We
reject the bashing of gays, Japan, rich people and immigrants that
contemporary liberals and conservatives seem to think addresses society's
problems,' they write. The doctrine ought to be acceptable to a broad swathe
of Americans, they claim, because it represents a return to the principles
that guided the nation's founding fathers: personal freedom, limited
government, free markets and the rule of law. What could be more American or
more traditional than that?
The book, however, is not without shortcomings. One danger is that
mainstream readers will be put off by the sheer radicalism of its specific
policy proposals. Mr Boaz, for example, would tackle inner city problems by
abolishing most welfare payments, legalising hard drugs and breaking up
public-sector educational monopolies. These are logically defensible
positions but pretty hard for any politician to defend.
There is little discussion of the broader obstacles preventing governments
from pursuing policies that are consistently liberal in the 19th century
sense. Boaz and Crane assume that the typical human being is a free spirit
looking for fresh challenges. But what if most people are risk averse and
keen on a relatively easy life? The essence of market liberalism is that
government should stand back and allow individuals to make a success or
failure of their lives. Crucial to this philosophy is the belief that people
should be allowed to fail. But the modern state largely exists to prevent or
limit people's ability to fail by providing pensions, healthcare, housing
and numerous other services. The evidence suggests these welfare cushions
are extremely popular.
Another obstacle is the modern world's deep commitment to social justice.
The most powerful objection to the prescriptions of true market liberals -
be they cutting marginal tax rates, scrapping minimum-wage laws or making
schools compete for pupils - is that they are 'unfair'. In the short run,
some individuals would gain at the expense of others; in the longer run the
gap between different income groups might widen. To make electoral progress,
market liberals have got to bring about a fundamental shift in popular
conceptions of fairness, for example by persuading people to stop worrying
about gaps in relative incomes.
This seems more possible in the US than in most of Europe. Indeed, at least
one possible presidential contender in 1996, Mr William Weld, the highly
regarded Republican governor of Massachusetts, is publicly associated with
the socially progressive/economically tough approach championed by Boaz and
Crane. A tax-cutting defender of gay rights, he even cites Friedrich Hayek,
the late Austrian economist, as one of his intellectual heroes. If Mr Weld
sticks to his principles and remains popular, he may come to represent the
future for the Republican party.
* Market Liberalism: A Paradigm for the 21st Century. Cato Institute, 1000
Mass Avenue NW, Washington DC 20001
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9199 General Government, NEC.
    P9111 Executive Offices.
</IN>
<XX>
