<PROFILE>_AN-DFACAADNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930601
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Revolution reconsidered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
By any prudent rule of thumb, revolutions are usually best avoided. They may
be exciting at the time, they may be inspiring later, but they are liable to
do much more harm than good. That's what my granny always said, so it must
be right.
History mostly backs her up. The French revolution was a national and
international calamity, and it is still not certain that France and Europe
have quite got over it. The Russian revolution was a direct descendant of
the French revolution, and no one is in any doubt of the scale of that
disaster, from which the Russians have yet to recover. Then there was the
Chinese cultural revolution. All in all, my granny's case seems pretty
conclusive.
And yet there are circumstances where what is needed is a total reform of
the whole system. Systems are by definition incapable of reforming
themselves from within; so if total reform is to take place at all, it must
be comprehensive, radical, and very fast - in short, a revolution. The
critical question, if the condemnation of history and my granny is to be
avoided, is whether such a revolution can be carried out without violence.
There are two places where this question may apply: Italy and Russia. In
Italy the conditions for transforming the corrupt political system have been
created from outside by the magistrates, who are keeping up the pressure by
arresting politicians and businessmen. But it is hard to shut out the idea
that last week's murderous car bomb in Florence may be an awful omen of just
how much may be at stake.
General system failure is much more comprehensive in Russia than in Italy.
But outsiders are perplexed to make sense of what is going on, because all
economists, east and west, and all governments, east and west, conspire to
tell us that the main issue at stake is economic reform.
That economic reform is a problem of enormous importance is not of course in
dispute. But there can be no doubt that by far the biggest issue is
political reform. Everyone knows the Russians are not doing too well on the
economic reform; but they cannot get the economics right because they are
not getting the politics right.
Ever since the Berlin wall came down, economic experts from east and west
have been arguing fiercely about the best way to make the transition from a
command to a market economy. 'Revolutionaries' said it should be fast and
radical; reformers said it should be slow and careful.
In theory, the revolutionaries have sold their case to the Moscow
government; in practice, the results so far have been pretty terrible, with
falling production, runaway money supply and rocketing inflation.
Critics say this seriously undermines the case for shock therapy. But Anders
Aslund from Sweden, who is a leading expert on Soviet and east European
economies, and also one of the leading advocates of shock therapy, thinks
there is a different explanation.
'The most conspicuously misunderstood part of the process of systemic change
in Russia', he says in a new report *, 'is the role of democratisation. . .
. In order to pursue any kind of change of economic system, or even run a
state, certain powers are required. . . . The best means for this purpose
was democratization.
'The key problem is that Russia has only had properly democratic
presidential elections. . . . Thus, stalled democratization is in fact the
major source of the economic failures to date.'
The Aslund analysis makes clear that the situation is much worse than a
simple stand-off between President Boris Yeltsin and a conservative
parliament, which thus prevents economic reform. On the contrary, the
tension between them is itself creating massive inflation and generating
systemic corruption and theft on a heroic scale.
First, the parliament demands inflationary expansion of bank credits to keep
state enterprises afloat. Second, the vast gap between inflation and
interest rates gives those with borrowing power (that is, the former
communist establishment) a great incentive to speculate in commodities.
Third, the remaining price controls on energy, raw materials and metals,
holding them well below world prices, create another a large incentive to
speculate, smuggle and steal.
'To judge from conversations with well-informed businessmen and government
officials', says Aslund, '10 to 20 per cent of the oil and at least
one-third of the metals exported from Russia in 1992 were smuggled out of
the country. Naturally the revenues from these sales stayed in bank accounts
abroad.' He estimates this capital flight at 'billions' of dollars.
Some people deplore the low level of foreign investment, especially in the
oil industry, which they explain by generally chaotic trading conditions.
But there is a more important reason - oil smugglers have no incentive to
accept foreign partners, who would stop their game.
Aslund's conclusion is that Russia still needs economic shock therapy. But
the prequisite for any strategy must be rapid democratization, because that
is the only way to break the power of the old nomenklatura.
The French revolution started with a debate on the bankrupt finances of the
state. The revolutionaries responded by issuing paper money on a vast and
rising scale. They tried to deal with the resulting inflation by price
controls. The consequence was famine. This led in turn to the terror.
* Systemic Change and Stabilization in Russia, by Anders Aslund; Royal
Institute of International Affairs
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
    RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9199 General Government, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 38
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-5924</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DFACAADMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930601
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Foreign Exchange and Money Markets Bundesbank caution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUNDESBANK council mem-bers have been hawkish in recent days about the
prospect for more German interest rate cuts, and that theme is likely to
continue this week, writes James Blitz.
There are now few expectations of the Bundesbank easing official rates at
its council meeting on Thursday.
Given the recent jump in M3 money supply growth, stubborn cost-of-living
inflation and the deterioration in public sector finances, the Bundesbank is
likely to be very cautious about its rate-cutting policy over the next few
weeks.
The release of indicators of west Germany's real economy in the next few
days should show signs of weakness in both industrial output and
manufacturing new orders - and this is likely to raise new questions about
how long the Bundesbank can keep monetary policy as tight as it currently
is.
However, Ms Ruth Lea of Mitsubishi Bank in London believes it is possible
that the rate of decline is now slowing down as Germany's export industries
are helped by growth in the US and by signs of green shoots in the UK.
Sterling weakened sharply in the wake of the cabinet reshuffle in the UK
last week, and dealers will be watching for any continuation of this trend.
Although the pound's weakness was mainly due to flows into the D-Mark, a
dealer said 'the rudderless feel' in UK economic policy meant that sterling
was being tossed around amid the turbulence in European currencies.
As ever, the non-farm payroll report in the US, due out on Friday, will be a
key indicator of the direction of the US economy and the dollar.
James Capel, based in London, is expecting a net rise of 115,000 in May's
headline figure.
</TEXT>
