<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Milan marks time awaiting Fiat
results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST bourses were shut for the Whitsun holiday, writes Our Markets Staff.
MILAN, which had only just absorbed Friday's disappointing results from
Montedison, awaited Fiat's 1992 figures, which were expected after the close
of business.
While most forecasts were for Fiat to announce a cut in its dividend for
1992 - estimates varied between a reduction of L80 and L150 from the 1991
dividend of L230 - some analysts commented that anything worse was likely to
lead to overall selling in the market today.
Fiat ordinary shares were L20 higher at L5,880, before slipping to L5,750 on
the kerb. The savings and privileged shares fell respectively by 2.5 per
cent and 3.6 per cent.
The Comit index ended 0.46 easier at 538.99. Montedison was fixed L25 lower
at L1,105 as a 30 per cent rise in first-quarter turnover helped to offset
the negative impact of a 1992 loss of L1,244bn.
Meanwhile, Ferruzzi, the holding group of Montedison, picked up L13 to
L1,076: it had reported a loss of L1,519bn after Friday's close.
Some brokers noted that investors had taken account of the conglomerate's
decision to seek outside shareholders in an effort to reduce debt.
Other gainers on the day included Stet, up L16 to L3,092, and Sip, ahead L20
at L1,976. Generali rose L80 to L36,780 but Olivetti lost L33 to L1,327.
In the banking sector, Credito Italiano advanced L59 to L2,974 and Banca
Commerciale Italiana put on L90 at L5,621.
MADRID's general index fell 1.58 to 257.19, one week before the June 6
general election. In London, Mr David Roche, global strategist at Morgan
Stanley, was inclined to believe that the fortunes of the Partido Populare,
rivalling the socialist incumbent led by Mr Felipe Gonzales, were looking up
ahead of last night's televised debates between the party leaders.
Looking at a number of post-election scenarios last Friday, Mr Roche said an
outright victory by the PP could lead to a push for growth, the float of the
peseta outside the ERM and a dramatic reduction in interest rates.
HELSINKI was quiet and the Hex index slipped 2.5 to 1,211.4 as turnover
dropped to FM97.8m from Friday's FM173.7m.
Some brokers observed that investors were awaiting interim reports, which
start to be published from tomorrow.
TEL AVIV's Mishtanim index retreated 2.45, or 1.2 per cent, to 203.34
following last week's gains, particularly in the banking sector.
