<DATE>930601
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / UK Gilts: Mood brightens in wake of auction success
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAST WEEK'S auction marked the switch to a more bullish view of the UK gilt
market.
The difference in sentiment compared with the sombre mood surrounding
April's auction was characterised in this way by Mr Chris Anthony, economist
at UBS: 'Last time, the economic data was strong, the pound was not doing
very well and there had been a downgrade of expectations on interest rates.'
Each of those factors looked different on Wednesday, although Thursday's
Cabinet reshuffle caused the pound to stumble.
On the economic front, the stream of relentlessly good news which increased
fears of inflation a few weeks ago has diminished. Last Friday's
announcement of a fall in the headline inflation rate to a mere 1.3 per cent
confirmed a more sanguine view, for this year at least.
Encouraging figures on unit labour costs and slower earnings growth have
also been seized on as the mood has veered towards optimism.
Even before Mr Kenneth Clarke became chancellor, sparking off speculation
about an interest rate cut, economists were saying pessimism on that front
had been overdone.
Forecasts that the base rate would come down from 6 per cent to 5 1/2 or 5
per cent by the end of the year remained common among both gilt-edged market
makers and fixed-income fund managers.
The theory is that signs of a faltering economic recovery plus lower
continental interest rates will allow a cut in the UK later this summer,
without undermining the pound.
Mr Simon Briscoe, economist at Greenwell Montagu, said speculation about a
rate cut 'fits in with the debate about funding. It will benefit the short
end of the curve and there is also speculation that the next issue will be
in the three to four-year area'.
Falling yields at the shorter end will steepen the yield curve, which is
seen as necessary to facilitate funding of the Pounds 50bn public sector
borrowing requirement.
Some economists believe this process will also involve an increase in yields
at the longer end to make issues in that area sufficiently attractive to
investors.
One economist forecast that yields on 20-year stock might have to rise from
the current level of about 8.5 per cent to 8.75 - 9 per cent.
He predicted that concerns about the pick-up in inflation would coincide
later this year with funding fatigue, bringing most pressure to bear at the
long end.
But views about that end of the market vary considerably, reflecting
divergent schools of thought on the inflation outlook.
One fixed income fund manager said the longer end looked attractive 'because
we are sanguine about inflation'. The forecast he was working to was 2.5 to
2.75 per cent for this year and less than 4 per cent - the ceiling on the
government's target - in 1994.
Views on whether or not that ceiling will be breached distinguish the 'oh
no, here we go again' school of inflation pessimists (or realists as they
would see themselves historically) from the 'it will be different this time'
optimists.
In terms of the attractiveness of gilts over the next few weeks, there is
more consensus and it tends to be positive.
An important part of this is the foreign interest being shown in the market,
one of the factors behind the auction's success.
Mr Chris Dillow, economist at Nomura, said the attractions to overseas
investors included the relatively weak currency, especially against the yen,
and the yield spread over other large bond markets.
In the 10-year benchmark area the yield spread over German bunds has
increased from less than 100 basis points in early April to more than 120.
The improvement in value compared with the French OAT is even more striking.
The difference has soared from less than 20 basis points in mid-February to
well over 80.
As Mr George Magnus, economist at SG Warburg, said last week, 'the big down
move from mid-March to a few days ago has been completed'.
The question is how long will the new upbeat mood last?
</TEXT>
