<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Risk and Reward: A model approach to underwriting fees in
rights issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE risks in underwriting positions justify the fees charged to companies in
rights offerings? Surely, with underwriting fees immutably fixed at 2 per
cent of the capital raised, regardless of the quality of the issuer,
something must be out of line.
Certainly, the Office of Fair Trading has mused over this point. Last year,
it announced an inquiry into underwriting fees and has still come to no firm
conclusions.
However, it has asked Professor Paul Marsh of the London Business School to
update a 1980 study into the profits earned by underwriters in rights
offerings.
Swiss Bank Corporation, meanwhile, says it has a technique for evaluating
the risks in an underwriting position which can more clearly demonstrate
where the pricing must be.
The model uses a derivatives approach to understanding a rights offering and
breaks the deal down into a series of put and call options.
Mr Brian Keelan, executive director at SBC, says that in a rights offering,
underwriters are simply selling companies a put option - the option to put
the shares to them at a given price - and issuing a call option to other
investors to call for the shares at a set price.
By studying the historic volatility in a given company's share price, it is
possible to determine whether or not the 2 per cent underwriting fee is
generous for the risk accepted or too stingy. Such analysis, which relies on
a Black Scholes model, is used to evaluate the pricing of other equity
options.
It was just such an approach that led SBC to make its controversial
intervention in an offering of enhanced scrip dividends by BAT, an offering
which had been designed by Barclays de Zoete Wedd.
Those dividends, designed to help BAT cut its bill for advance corporation
tax, gave investors the choice of a cash payout or a payout in new shares
having a value 50 per cent above the cash option.
And for those who did not wish to keep the extra shares, BZW offered to buy
them, with no transaction costs, at 5 per cent below the market price
determined by the average of three days closing prices.
But SBC, using its derivative model, said it found 5 per cent far too
generous to the underwriter and realised it could still do the deal
profitably by repurchasing the shares at only a 2 per cent discount.
SBC said it used the technique to evaluate a rights offering by Trafalgar
House last February and concluded the pricing offered was generous. SBC had
earlier used an options model to help its client, Hong Kong Land, build a
stake in Trafalgar House so it had already researched the historic
volatility in the company's share price.
An SBC official said that at the time of the offering, put and call options
on TH traded on the London Traded Options Market suggested a volatility of
70 per cent, meaning the price could rise or fall 70 per cent in a year. But
using its own proprietary data base, SBC concluded the volatility was
actually much lower, thus, the options were probably priced too high.
The TH rights offering, a two-for-one deal, gave new shares at 60p each
against a pre-rights offering price of 78p, a discount of 24 per cent. The
price of the put option to TH is effectively the 2 per cent underwriting
fee. An SBC official, citing the London Business School's own options data
base, shows that the volatility by that measure is a much more modest 40 per
cent. And at that rate, a price of .012 per cent would have been sufficient
to cover the risk in that underwriting.
SBC's analysis of the differences in rights offerings may be purely
academic. There is no suggestion underwriters have either the incentive or
the muscle to begin to compete with each other on underwriting fees.
For one thing, the institutional shareholders who sub-underwrite the deals
are unlikely ever to agree to it. But certainly, the maturation of the
equity derivatives market could help to call into question the whole issue
of the valuation of rights offerings.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Swiss Bank Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
