<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / International Company News: IRI chief to take charge of Stet
telecoms unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michele Tedeschi, mana-ging director of Italy's IRI state holding
company, is to become managing director of its Stet telecommunications
subsidiary in a surprise transfer.
The change reinforces signs that IRI, which reported a 1992 loss of L4,809bn
(Dollars 3.27bn) and faces group debts of about L73,000bn, will be whittled
down while Stet and Finmeccanica, its two biggest subsidiaries, gain weight.
Both companies are already stock market listed and are set to be
progressively privatised.
It also confirms that Mr Romano Prodi, IRI's chairman until 1989, who was
reappointed last month will now take full control of running the group.
Under a 1992 restructuring which marked Mr Tedeschi's promotion to managing
director, the chairman was relegated to a largely representational role
while the managing director was given mainstream management
responsibilities.
Mr Prodi did not indicate any desire to change matters after his
re-appointment and seemed content with the role of IRI's 'ambassador' to the
business and finance community. However, under yesterday's changes, he will
assume Mr Tedeschi's powers as soon as the latter is transfered later this
week.
Mr Tedeschi, who has started reshaping IRI, faces the task of restructuring
Stet, which controls Italy's state-owned telecoms activities. The sector,
split between seven companies, is due to be rationalised by the end of 1995.
The process, likely to meet stiff management and political resistance, is an
important step in the government's privatisation plans, with the eventual
single utility, tentatively called Telecom Italia, one of the most
attractive privatisation candidates.
Mr Tedeschi's move will also create ructions within the highly-politicised
Stet group, where there are two managing directors, both of whom will be
reassigned.
Mr Biagio Agnes was yesterday reconfirmed as Stet's chairman, but he will
also see his role diminished.
</TEXT>
