FT  01 JUN 93 / International Company News: First-quarter recovery at
Skandia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SKANDIA, one of Sweden's two leading insurers, showed a strong recovery in
the first quarter, as it posted a SKr700m (Dollars 95m) operating profit
compared with a SKr300m loss in the same period of 1992.
The result, which includes unrealised changes in asset values, was struck
after premium income rose to SKr11.7bn from SKr9.6bn, largely because of
increased life insurance business.
The figures were provided by Mr Bjorn Wolrath, Skandia chief executive, at
the group's annual general meeting.
The group's net asset value is estimated to have risen to SKr12.6bn from
SKr11.4bn at the year-end, thanks to rising share and bond prices and
exchange rate movements. It saw a 20 per cent fall in net asset value last
year which prompted the company to suspend its dividend for the first time
in its history.
Skandia said its position is also being strengthened by its decision to
reduce non-life reinsurance operations, which should help boost its solvency
margin to 65 per cent by the year-end, compared with 51 per cent at the end
of 1992.
