FT  01 JUN 93 / International Company News: Shares in Moksel suspended due
to fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Moksel, the large German meat-processing company, were suspended
last week shortly before the Bavaria-based group announced it had been the
victim of a DM100m (Dollars 62m) fraud in a company bought last year.
Moksel said on Friday it had discovered 'major irregularities' in the
accounts of Salomon, a meat company with sales of DM500-DM600m bought last
year, as well as evidence of 'dishonest acts'.
The fraud appeared to have been perpetrated over a period of years before
the acquisition, and Moksel said a total of around DM100m appeared to have
gone missing.
Moksel said it would be in the best interests of the company if it paid no
dividend for 1992. The plan had been to pay DM11 per share. It said that
beyond this it did not expect the fraud to have any other financial
repercussions.
Moksel's sales last year fell from DM4.02bn in 1991 to DM3.7bn despite
several acquisitions. The drop reflected changing demand from eastern
Germany.
