FT  01 JUN 93 / International Company News: CSR net profit increased by 20%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CSR, the Australian building products, sugar and aluminium group, yesterday
announced an rise of 20 per cent in net profit to ADollars 211.2m (USDollars
148.3m) for the year to end-March, on revenue up 9 per cent to ADollars
4.3bn.
The group said higher sugar prices and an improvement in productivity
outweighed the effects of low aluminium prices and patchy economic recovery
in its main markets in Australia and the US.
Its sugar mills made substantially higher profits because of a record sugar
cane crop and higher world prices.
The timber products division returned to profit after two years of losses.
These gains were partly offset by lower prices and profit margins in
Australia for some building products.
However, the bottom line was boosted by a net abnormal profit of ADollars
20m, mainly due to a restatement of provisions against income tax
liabilities, resulting in net profit after abnormals of ADollars 231.3m.
This was in sharp contrast to 1991-1992, when a change in accounting
standards forced the group to write down the value of assets by ADollars
560m, resulting in a loss after abnormals of ADollars 385.3m.
The final dividend was lifted from 10 to 12 cents, fully franked, making 22
cents for the year, against 20 cents.
