</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TRELLEBORG, the Swedish mining and industrial group, fell heavily into the
red in the first four months after being hit by depressed metals prices and
losses from associated companies.
It made a loss of SKr427m (Dollars 58m) after financial items, compared with
SKr187m profit in the same 1992 period, as operating income slipped to
SKr7.80bn from SKr7.95bn.
The group warned it would suffer another 'severe deficit' in 1993, after
last year's SKr1.56bn loss, because of weak business conditions and its US
dollar hedging.
'The first four months were characterised by record low metal prices and
continued decline in the building market,' the company said. Business
conditions in Sweden and Europe remained weak, while the US market had not
shown any sign of an upturn.
The result was aggravated by a SKr121m loss from associated companies,
against a SKr134m profit last year, while exchange gains at SKr7m were
SKr215m less than a year ago. There was a loss after depreciation of SKr13m,
against a SKr103m profit in 1992.
</TEXT>
