<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / International Company News: Statistical reports circulate
under great secrecy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Every summer for the past 21 years, bundles of documents stacked a foot high
have circulated under conditions of great secrecy around City financial
institutions.
More than 200 banks, brokerages and consultants in London pay upwards of
Pounds 30,000 for these detailed statistical reports and consulting advice
to back them up.
While the anuual Extel ratings of analysts - the industry's own assessment
of its peers - circulate freely around the City, the companies are far more
coy about revealing these findings to their competitors or the Press.
The money spent does not give them carte blanche to use the findings. They
sign a confidentiality agreement and agree that they are renting rather than
buying the reports.
The company responsible is Greenwich Associates, a US consulting and market
research business based in Greenwich, Connecticut. Each year it comes to
London and other big financial centres around the world to conduct
interviews with institutions and canvass their views on how they are
serviced.
'This is the bible,' says one senior figure in a large City securities
house, tapping one of the reports, which is firmly closed. 'It is very hard
to run a firm without it. It is invaluable if you know how to understand the
figures. Luckily not many of our competitors do.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
