<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / BAe may sell business jets to Raytheon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Aerospace is in advanced negotiations to sell its corporate jet
activities to Raytheon, the US company that makes Beechcraft small and
business aircraft.
Although BAe yesterday described the talks as 'speculation', the UK
aerospace group has already attempted to sell control of its business jet
operations to Raytheon last year.
After the original deal collapsed last September, BAe announced it intended
to hold on to its business jet division whose headquarters were transferred
from the UK to Little Rock, Arkansas, a leading centre for executive jets.
However, Mr Dick Evans, BAe's chief executive, also said last year the
company no longer regarded its business aircraft operations as a core
activity. It has also continued seeking a buyer for its business jet
division and negotiations with Raytheon and its Beechcraft subsidiary are
understood to have been gathering steam in recent weeks.
BAe's business aircraft activities are estimated to be worth around Pounds
200m to Pounds 250m, according to City of London analysts. A sale would
provide BAe with valuable cash at a time of extensive restructuring.
The sale of the business aircraft activities would also reflect the general
trend of consolidation in the corporate aircraft sector which has seen a
number of deals in the last 12 months including the take over of Cessna by
Textron of the US and of Learjet by Bombardier of Canada.
BAe's corporate jet business would also provide Raytheon's Beechcraft
subsidiary with a good fit since Beechcraft is in the lower end of the
market and BAe's operations would enable it to expand its business in the
medium-range corporate jet market.
BAe manufactures the 125/800 and the 125/1000 medium-size business jets.
This has been a successful activity for the UK company for the past 30
years. But the 125 family of aircraft now requires heavy investment to renew
its product line and BAe no longer considers this a strategic option in its
recovery programme.
Instead, BAe is refocusing its aerospace operations around its military
aircraft activities and its 20 per cent stake in the European Airbus
airliner programme.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Aerospace.
    Raytheon.
</CO>
<XX>
