<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Japanese steel groups predict return to red in first half
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE steel companies expect to slip into loss again this year, a decade
after they launched restructuring and diversification programmes intended to
strengthen the industry in the face of falling steel demand.
Nippon Steel, the world's largest steel maker, reported a 71.2 per cent
plunge to Y28.9bn (Pounds 170m) in pre-tax profit for year ended in March,
and forecast a first-half loss of Y5bn this year. It is hoping an eventual
economic recovery will produce a full-year profit of about Y20bn.
Other leading makers, including Kawasaki Steel, Kobe Steel, and Sumitomo
Metal Industries, also predicted first-half losses of about Y5bn, but
suggested a change in economic conditions in the second half would return
them to the black.
NKK would have reported a loss last year but for a Y17.4bn gain on sales of
securities holdings. Pre-tax profit fell 89 per cent to Y4.1bn, while net
profit plunged 99 per cent to Y255m. It expects a first-half pre-tax loss of
Y15bn this year.
Pre-tax profits at Kobe were down 69.6 per cent, at Kawasaki by 82.5 per
cent and Sumitomo Metal by 86.9 per cent. Each of the companies is
attempting to cut costs and reduce staff after much heralded diversification
programmes failed to add to profitability during another downturn in demand.
Crude steel production at Nippon Steel was down almost 10 per cent to 25,320
tons and would have fallen further had import orders from China not tripled
during the year.
</TEXT>
