<DATE>930601
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / People: Barclays' high-flyer moves offshore
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Barclays has moved one of its young high-flyers into the growing private
banking operation, making Catherine McDowell, previously head of investor
relations, its first director specifically responsible for offshore banking.
Based in the Mayfair headquarters of the private banking division, she joins
its management board headed by Michael Tomalin, managing director.
Private banking is increasingly in vogue with UK high street banks as a way
of increasing income without tying up large amounts of capital.
John Church, another director within the private bank, says that the
offshore centres - including Jersey, Guernsey, the Isle of Man, and
Gibraltar - represent a 'very substantial part' of the division's overall
operations.
While traditionally strongest on the trust and fiduciary side, Barclays is
now keen to offer an integrated service from banking through to investment
management. McDowell has responsibilities for service and product
development in addition to her geographic beat.
Joining Barclays Bank International as a graduate trainee in 1978, McDowell,
just 35, has gathered considerable experience around the group. In 1984 she
moved to New York where she worked in the treasury division before being
seconded to BZW Securities, also on Wall Street, marketing to US pension
funds and other institutional investors.
Since 1991 she has been head of investor relations, traditionally a job for
the bank's fast-track executives. Her watch however has been a particularly
challenging one - a period during which the bank has been hit by a series of
bad loans and been the subject of intense scrutiny from its institutional
shareholders over senior management succession.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Barclays.
</CO>
