<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Construction Contracts: European road research development
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
TRAFALGAR HOUSE TECHNOLOGY has started work on a Europe-wide research
project to develop a cementitious overlay for repairing flexible road
pavements.
The Ecu3.06m (Pounds 2.38m) project is aimed at combating the growing
problem of rutting in asphalt pavements caused by increasing axle loads,
higher tyre pressures and growing traffic volume. Known as NEWPAVE, the
research will be of interest to all European countries who currently devote
a substantial amount of their transport budgets to road maintenance.
The European Commission's Brite-EuRam programme is providing 50 per cent of
the project's funds with the rest coming from a consortium made up of seven
organisations.
Besides THT, the consortium consists of the UK's Transport Research
Laboratory, two Danish companies, Aalborg Portland A/S and Dansk Beton
Teknik A/S, the Danish Road Institute, the Technical University of Denmark
and the National Civil Engineering Laboratory of Portugal.
The overlay material being developed by NEWPAVE will be used both as a
wearing course and strengthening for flexible road pavements.
</TEXT>
