<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Economics: Unemployment data expected to show gloomy state
of Europe's labour market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE problem of high unemployment will be taxing the minds of ministers from
the world's leading industrial nations this week, as a string of poor
unemployment data is expected in Germany, Belgium, Denmark, Finland and the
US.
The European figures are likely to confirm the gloomy state of the
continent's labour market, while in the US the markets will be nervously
watching non-farm payroll figures at the end of the week.
The OECD has already announced that unemployment will be one of the issues
dominating the ministerial meeting in Paris on Wednesday and Thursday. In
their discussions, ministers from over 20 countries will focus on promoting
sustainable economic growth, but with the emphasis on the current bad
employment situation, particularly within the European Community.
There will also be discussions on trade as world recession has prompted
countries to become more protectionist. The release of industrial output
figures in Germany this week will come as a timely reminder of the
sluggishness of world growth.
The output figures are forecast to show that economic activity in west
Germany is being depressed by high interest rates even though these are
gradually being eased by the Bundesbank. Some economists are suggesting,
however, that the rate of economic decline in Germany is slowing as
Germany's export industries are helped by continuing growth in the US and
signs of recovery in the UK.
In the US, May non-farm payrolls are expected to show fairly healthy rise.
Economists believe most of the jobs growth will have come from the service
sector. The unemployment rate should remain unchanged at 7 per cent.
The following are the week's other economic highlights and events. Figures
in brackets are the median of economists' forecasts from MMS International,
the financial information company.
Yesterday: Europe, most markets closed. Canada, March real GDP (up 0.3 per
cent on month). Japan, April industrial production (down 2.6 per cent),
shipments, construction orders, housing starts (up 5.6 per cent on year),
construction starts. Australia, April current account, building approvals.
Today: France, Franco-German summit with Mitterrand and Balladur both
representing France. US, May NAPM index (50.4 per cent); April personal
income (up 0.2 per cent), construction spending (up 0.9 per cent); Johnson
Redbook week ended May 29. Japan, March leading diffusion index, coincident
index; May wholesale prices index - second 10 days. Australia, Q4 gross
national expenditure (up 0.5 per cent on quarter), Q4 GDP (up 0.5 per cent
on quarter); Reserve Bank of Australia monthly board meeting. Singapore,
markets closed.
Tomorrow: France, OECD council meets at ministerial level. Meeting lasts
until Thursday. UK, May official reserves (up Pounds 100m), M0 (down 0.7 per
cent on month, up 3.7 per cent on year). Germany, Bundesbank makes address
to German Banks. US, April leading indicator (up 0.3 per cent), new home
sales (650,000). Canada, May Help Wanted Index (89).
Thursday: Germany, Bundesbank council meeting in Frankfurt, Q1 GDP - west
(down 1.5 per cent). US, initial claims week ended May 29 (340,000); state
benefits week ended May 22; money supply data for week ended May 24. Canada,
May foreign reserves. Japan, April current account, trade balance, foreign
bond investment.
Friday: Germany, May unemployment - west (up 40,000), vacancies (down
3,000), short time work - east (down 15,000), unemployment - east (down
22,000); April employment - west (down 50,000). Spain, May official reserves
(Dollars 15bn). US, May non-farm payrolls (up 150,000), manufacturing
payrolls (up 10,000), hourly earnings (up 0.3 per cent), average workweek,
civil unemployment rate (7 per cent); April factory orders (up 0.2 per
cent), factor inventories. Canada, May employment (up 0.2 per cent on
month), unemployment rate (11.2 per cent).
During the week: Germany, April industrial production (down 0.5 per cent on
month), manufacturing output (down 0.5 per cent on month), manufacturing
orders (down 0.5 per cent on month). Belgium, May unemployment rate (12.3
per cent). Italy, May CPI (up 4.1 per cent on year). Denmark, April
unemployment rate (12.1 per cent). Switzerland, May CPI for Zurich and
Federation.
