<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Management (The Growing Business): Negotiating the barriers
 -Charles Batchelor continues a series answering questions on the European
single market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Growing Business Page's Single Market Q&amp;A series is intended to allow
readers to raise issues prompted by the formal launch of the single European
market on January 1 1993
In theory the barriers have come down in Europe but in practice doing
business across borders can be complex and time consuming.
FINDING COMPATIBLE QUALIFICATIONS
Q: We are consulting civil and structural engineers engaged in several
design projects in Germany. In order to obtain the necessary building permit
approval we have been using a local German consultant to sign our design
documentation. However, if we could establish that the various engineering
qualifications were compatible within the EC then we would not need to
employ the middle-man and would be more cost efficient.
What is the relationship between the German Dipl. Ing. degree qualifications
and the British Chartered Engineer status?
A: The German Dipl. Ing. is an academic qualification obtained after at
least three years of study. In Britain, the title of Chartered Engineer is
gained on the successful completion of a degree (accredited by a nominated
institution of the Engineering Council), as well as two years training and
two years relevant experience.
To obtain building permit approval in Germany a British engineer would have
to prove a theoretical qualification - at least three years of study and at
least two years of practice in the required field. The engineer would then
apply to the regional Architektenkammer (chamber of architects) which would
verify documentation and include the engineer on the official list of
architects.
Once on the architects list the engineer should be able to obtain approvals
from the Bauordnungs amt (office for building regulations).
Each German Land has its own building regulations, so British engineers must
apply to the chamber of architects in the Land where they want to work.
However, once an engineer has been recognised in one Land there should be no
problem in obtaining recognition in another.
Freedom to work anywhere in the EC is one of the basic rights laid down by
the Treaty of Rome. The first general directive (89/48/EEC) on the freedom
of establishment of professionals was adopted in 1989. It applies to any
profession regulated in some way by the state and for which at least three
years full-time education and training at university or equivalent level is
required. Among professions covered are lawyers, accountants, teachers,
engineers and physiotherapists.
COMPENSATION FOR RELOCATION
Q: Is there any EC legislation governing the allocation of monetary
compensation to staff as part of a relocation package. I am an American
national, the head office of my company is in Holland and I will be moving
from the Far East to Austria.
A: No EC legislation has been proposed in this area. In the situation
outlined it is probable that the Dutch parent company has general employment
policy guidelines in line with EC employment law. However, those guidelines
would have to conform to Austrian labour law. Austria is not a member of the
Community.
GUIDE FOR WINE IMPORTERS
Q: I wish to import wine from France. Is there a reference book containing
the names and addresses of growers/negotiants in France? What are the VAT
implications on the purchase and export of wine for commercial purposes?
Does a current list of wholesale wines exist?
A: A reference book titled Grappe lists the producers/negotiants by
wine-growing region and covers all of France. This appears to be the most
complete publication of its type and is published by Vininfo at 30 Quai des
Chartrons, 33000 Bordeaux, at a cost of FFr680 (Pounds 80). Vininfo also
offers the information in computerised form, charged at FFr1.40 per address.
French VAT is payable at time of purchase in France if the producer is not
registered for VAT in the UK. Otherwise, VAT is payable on importation into
the UK.
There does not appear to be a centralised list of current wholesale prices
covering all French wines. However, the Bordeaux vineyard publishes an
annual list of average prices per barrel for each wine-growing region. In
addition, the Burgundy/Macon vineyard compiles a list of wholesale prices
for different vintages. For these lists contact: Conseil Interprofessionnel
des Vins de Bordeaux, 1 Cours du XXX Juillet, 33075 Bordeaux. Tel: 56 00 22
66. Fax: 56 00 22 77. Comite Interprofessionnel des Vins de Bourgogne/Macon,
Maison de la Saone et Loire, 389 Ave. du Mal de Lattre de Tassigny, 71000
Macon. Tel: 85 38 20 15.
General information on the labelling, bottling, packaging and documentation
of wine imported into the UK is available from the Wine and Spirit
Association of Great Britain at 1 Queen Street Place, London EC4R 1XX. Tel:
071 248 5377.
PENSIONS POSE PORTABILITY PROBLEM
Q: I am looking for clarification of the position of someone with a UK
company pension who wishes to work in another EC member state.
Is it possible to take out a pension in one member state while working
elsewhere in the Community? It seems strange that the funds paid in by
individuals to pension schemes can be used by pension companies and invested
across the Community while the individuals providing these funds do not have
the same freedom.
A: No, it is not possible to maintain a pension taken out in one member
state if you move permanently to work in another.
This continuation of pension contributions is not prevented by EC
legislation but by national legislation. For example, UK tax law states
that, unless you are taxable in the UK on your earnings, pension
contributions are disallowed. However, if you maintain your taxable status
and residency in the UK then you can continue to contribute. This refers to
both company and private pensions.
Although there is a movement towards finding a solution to the restrictions
you mention, there has been very little development in terms of
harmonisation and the portability of pension schemes throughout the
Community. This is mainly because of the diversity of pensions schemes that
exist in the member states and as a result national legislation prevails.
If you are moving permanently to one of the member states, it might be
possible to arrange for a transfer of your UK pension rights to a scheme set
up by your new employer. However, this would depend on the structure of your
existing pension scheme. The same applies to private pension schemes. It is
only possible to transfer your pension if a complementary system exists in
the country you move to.
If, however, you are posted temporarily by your employers to work in another
member state it is possible to remain in the UK company pension scheme for
up to 10 years.
If you move abroad permanently and you are no longer paying UK income tax
nor earning as a resident of the UK, the simplest course of action would be
to allow your UK company scheme to continue to grow tax free. A number of UK
pension providers offer off-shore pension plans to expatriates.
In the UK there are no restrictions on the investment of pension funds
within the Community. However, restrictions of this kind of operation do
exist in other member states. A draft directive on the investment of pension
funds across the Community is currently being considered by an EC Council
working party.
SEEKING INFORMATION ON SOURCES OF FUNDING
Q: We are looking for information on EC sources of funding for companies for
research and development programmes, training and business development.
A: There is such a wide range of EC programmes in these areas that it is
best to refer to one of the detailed publications available.
A Guide to the European Community Grants and Loans, compiled by Tony Reid,
Eurofi PLC, Guildgate House, Pelican Lane, Newbury, Berkshire, RG13 INK.
Tel: 0635 31900. 340 pages. Price Pounds 140.
Finance from Europe: A Guide to Grants and Loans from the European
Community, compiled for the London Office of the European Commission.
Currently being revised. 32 pages. Free.
These can be examined at your local European Information Centre and at many
business libraries.
Previous features in this series appeared on May 4 and March 9.
If you have any queries relating to doing business in Europe or to the
changes brought about by the creation of the single European market, please
write to:
Charles Batchelor
Single Market Q&amp;A
Number One, Southwark Bridge
London, SE1 9HL
or fax 071 873 3933
This feature has been compiled with the assistance of the European
Information Centre of the London Chamber of Commerce.
</TEXT>
