FT  01 JUN 93 / Power station may be sold
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NUCLEAR Electric, the state-owned nuclear power generator, is preparing to
put the disused Bankside power station in Southwark, south London, on the
market, Vanessa Houlder writes.
The building is more likely to be demolished than converted, although the
Tate Gallery has considered housing a gallery in it.
The 6m cu ft brick structure was built on an 8 1/2 acre Thames-side site in
1957. It was recently given a certificate of immunity from listing and its
future depends on the planning brief to be negotiated with the local
authority.
The building was one of the assets given to Nuclear Electric when it was
created. The company has paid Pounds 2.5m for the removal of asbestos, with
which it was contaminated.
