<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Plans for social fund under fire
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOVES BY the European Commission to broaden the remit of the European Social
Fund will reduce the amount of money spent on training the long-term
unemployed, the government says.
The Department of Employment is opposed to the proposal, which would affect
the distribution of the Pounds 250m a year received by the UK for the
unemployed.
Brussels wants to reform objectives three and four of the social fund,
devoted to training the young, the long-term unemployed, women with
disabilities and women returning to the labour market.
It wants its funding to provide added value to labour-market measures rather
than to provide a subsidy to national unemployment schemes. And it wants to
direct money to the retraining needs of industries in decline or change.
The aim is to reskill workers before they become unemployed and smooth their
transition into alternative employment - a move seen by the UK government as
a disguised industrial policy.
The department said in a consultation document issued to bodies including
local authorities and training and enterprise councils that the government
was opposed to the new objective four - which was 'to facilitate the
adaptation of workers to industrial change and to changes in production
systems.'
This was unlikely to yield good value for money, as in the UK about two
thirds of the unemployed left the unemployment register within six months,
it said.
</TEXT>
