<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Lib Dems suggest early end to mortgage tax relief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN END TO mortgage-interest tax relief for home buyers in the future is
envisaged in a housing policy paper published by the Liberal Democrats
yesterday.
The document makes it clear, however, that the tax break would continue for
all those who currently receive it. For everyone else it would be replaced
by a new benefit - housing cost relief - which would be available both to
home owners and to tenants on the basis of need.
While the party's policy is that mortgage-interest relief should simply be
allowed to wither over 10 to 25 years, the paper also floats the option of
phasing it out over five years, to release the money saved for other
projects.
In particular, it suggests that the immediate end to mortgage-interest tax
relief could save Pounds 5.2bn in the first year, which could be used to cut
the basic rate of income tax or to build new homes.
Government help for people who have fallen behind with mortgage payments or
who have mortgages above the current value of their homes is also proposed
as an alternative use for the savings.
One of the aims of the policies in the paper is to end the bias towards home
ownership and to allow people the opportunity to move between rented
property and owner-occupation in either direction.
The Conservatives share the objective of reviving the private rented sector
but the question of mortgage-interest relief is so politically contentious
that Tory campaigners believe the paper will provide them with valuable
material to use against the Liberal Democrats.
The paper also proposes:
A reformed and more generous housing benefit system.
Greater accountability for housing associations by separating the monitoring
and financial roles of the housing corporation.
The introduction of 'partnership housing' to bridge the gap between normal
housing association rents and the private rented sector.
</TEXT>
