FT  01 JUN 93 / Kalms backs ethics studies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR STANLEY KALMS, the chairman of high-street electrical goods retailer
Dixons, has donated money for the promotion of ethics to another two
academic institutions.
One beneficiary is the Shalom Hartman Institute in Jerusalem, which will
consider how to apply Jewish beliefs to the modern world.
Mr Kalms would not specify the amount, but said: 'It is an open-ended
commitment.'
The donation follows his announcement last month that he had given money to
the University of North London - formerly the Polytechnic of North London -
to help fund a readership in business ethics and strategic management.
The university said that his contribution, from the Stanley Kalms
Foundation, will amount to about Pounds 10,000 a year for three years.
Last July he made a donation of Pounds 1m from Dixons to the London Business
School for a chair in business ethics and social responsibility.
There are already two other related academic posts in the UK: the DBM chair
in corporate governance at Leeds University and the Co-Operative Bank chair
of corporate responsibility at Manchester University.
Mr Kalms originally offered the money to the economics department at the
London School of Economics, which he said declined the offer, saying that
such a subject properly belonged in the philosophy department.
There has been some concern about the way in which the interviews for the
chair at the London Business School have been conducted, with little
advertising, no job description and long delays before unsuccessful
candidates were notified.
But Mr Andrew Likierman, a professor who sits on the appointment committee,
said yesterday: 'I am very very happy to defend everything about this
appointment. Everything has been above-board.'
