<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Number of Lloyd's agencies 'to fall sharply'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of agencies at Lloyd's of London is set to fall sharply as new
corporate investors demand much higher standards of advice and service, a
new report has concluded.
Mr Oliver Laughton-Scott, director of De Lisle Jessup Scott, the insurance
consultancy which prepared the report, said: 'This is Lloyd's big bang.'
Lloyd's announced at the end of April that it hoped to attract incorporated
capital by the start of next year as part of its new business plan. It is
preparing a rulebook which will outline the terms on which 'incorporated
Names' - which will trade on the basis of limited liability - can
participate.
The report suggests that the number of members' agencies - which handle the
affairs of the individual Names who provide the market's capital - at the
market could eventually fall to as low as eight. Seventy members' agents
traded at Lloyd's last year, compared with 83 in 1991.
The report suggests corporate investors will demand rigorous information
about the market when they choose which of the market's 200 or more
syndicates to support.
Members' agents and Lloyd's advisers will need to be big enough to bear the
costs of providing necessary analytical and advisory services and maintain a
broad spread of investors. 'The requirement for a higher standard of
analysis is likely to put smaller members' agents under increasing
pressure,' the report says.
It suggests that agencies which combine members' and managing agent
functions - where they both look after the Names who provide the market's
capital and manage syndicates - will find it increasingly difficult to
survive. The number of so-called 'combined agencies' fell from 37 in 1991 to
32 last year.
Pointing to the ability of combined agencies to sustain their own syndicates
by channelling capital towards them, the report says new corporate investors
'will be more alert to the inherent conflicts of interest' and 'are likely
to require firmer safeguards'.
Additionally, members' agents which are part of combined agencies may find
access to detailed information from rival managing agents more difficult
than independent members' agents, it says.
The report is sceptical of Lloyd's ability to ration capacity available to
new investors through an auction or bidding system.
'The proposed auction system will require investors to bid for participation
without being able to guarantee participation on specific syndicates. This
will prove unacceptable to potential investors,' the report says.
</TEXT>
