<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Price advantages are slipping away: Exporters fear the
recession in Europe is cutting into gains made from a weak pound
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, KEVIN DONE, DANIEL GREEN, PAUL ABRAHAMS, ANDREW
BAXTER and PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH industrialists are warning that the full potential for an export-led
recovery in the UK is starting to be undermined by the widespread recession
affecting European markets.
Last year's devaluation of sterling has already provided a sharp boost to UK
exports outside the European Community, government statistics show. But in
spite of evidence of strengthening sales for many companies in continental
Europe - an area that accounts for one-third of UK exports - there are fears
that export growth is starting to be hit by weakening demand.
Some UK companies are managing to achieve larger market shares because of
increased competitiveness, although they warn that any further appreciation
of sterling could remove the price advantage for British products. Other
businesses say higher sales are being accompanied by lower selling prices
and smaller margins.
Sir Michael Angus, president of the Confederation of British Industry, said:
'There are clouds on the horizon. The prospects for exports to Europe are
now suffering a severe squeeze as the main European economies fall into
recession.'
Nine months after sterling's withdrawal from the exchange rate mechanism
businesses believe improved competitiveness is being increasingly offset by
poor trading conditions.
The sharp fall in sales of new vehicles in continental Europe, for example,
is hitting exports by UK car producers such as Ford and General Motors'
subsidiary Vauxhall.
The impact on the overall UK car export effort will be softened, however, by
the rapid increase of UK production by the three Japanese carmakers Nissan,
Honda and Toyota. All three producers are aiming to export about three
quarters of their UK car output.
The UK operations of GM and Ford are more exposed to falling European sales
as they have recently started exporting a significant share of their output.
In spite of improved UK demand, Vauxhall's UK assembly plants have
introduced short-time working in the face of the steep decline in European
demand. But with UK plants providing the lower cost base, the deeper cuts
are more likely in Europe.
Ford, which last year exported more than half of the output from its
Dagenham, Essex plant, is becoming increasingly concerned that the fall in
new car sales in Germany, France, Italy and Spain will hit UK production.
Rover believes that the devaluation of sterling has given it a strong
competitive advantage in continental Europe this year and that gains in
market share will cushion the fall in the overall European market.
Mr Richard Robson, managing director of Fermec Holdings, the construction
equipment manufacturer that exports to Europe, says that on balance his
business has gained from recent events. 'If the gain is 100, the offset is
about 70, which comes equally from the weakness in Continental markets,
particularly France and Germany, and from the higher cost of imported
components from Denmark and Germany.'
Mr Malcolm Taylor, managing director of Bridgeport Machines, one of the UK's
largest machine tool makers, said devaluation and the internal problems of
the German machine tool industry handed his company 'a tremendous
advantage'.
He added: 'Our German sales had grown significantly over the past three
years and it was becoming our best European market. The problem is that
nobody there is buying machine tools now.'
The chemicals sector reports the same experience. Mr Richard Freeman, chief
economist at Imperial Chemical Industries, said: 'The slowdown in demand,
particularly in Germany, has been partly offset by the benefits of
devaluation. But weak demand is having the effect of undermining prices in
all the basic chemicals. Exports are getting through but not in the
quantities they ought to be.'
Textile and clothing exporters to Europe report that recession is already
outweighing the benefits of price competitiveness.
Mr Ronald Miller, chairman of Dawson International, the luxury knitwear
manufacturer, reported a 20 per cent fall in sales in France in spite of a
distinct price edge from devaluation. The company has managed to raise sales
in Germany but at the expense of margins.
Mr Neville Bain, chief executive of Coats Viyella, Britain's largest textile
manufacturer, said European profits were likely to be lower this year, with
the climate in Germany and France 'very difficult'.
Marks and Spencer, the UK retailer through which Britain's clothing
manufacturers export almost Pounds 150m-worth of goods to Europe, said heavy
competition for sales was forcing price cuts - of up to 30 per cent in
Holland, for example.
For the UK-based spirit companies profit margins are under pressure as
consumer spending dips across Europe. Grand Metropolitan's growth in Europe
has slowed since last autumn in the face of recession in important markets
such as Spain, France and Germany.
Mr Colin Hope, chairman of T&amp;N, the UK automotive components groups, echoed
many industrialists in calling for a period of exchange-rate stability so
that gains in market share could be consolidated.
He said: 'Our German competitors are losing money and still they are cutting
prices to compete with us. The Germans are fighting a big rearguard action.
In this situation it would be a shame if the pound were to harden against
the D-Mark because that could stop the build-up of orders.'
The CBI said that for the moment its members were not unhappy about the
value of the pound. But if it went much higher industry would again be
banging on the Treasury's door demanding action.
</TEXT>
