<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / TUC to act over pay bias against union members
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TRADES Union Congress plans to complain to the International Labour
Organisation about a controversial amendment in the government's new labour
legislation allowing employers to discriminate against trade unionists by
denying them wage rises if they refuse to sign personal contracts.
Mr Norman Willis, the TUC's general secretary, has written to Mr David Hunt,
the new employment secretary, pointing out that 'the amendment, if it passes
into law, would clearly be a violation of ILO convention 98 on the right to
organise and collective bargaining.
'I sincerely hope the government will abandon the amendment,' Mr Willis
says. If not, the TUC will lodge a formal complaint with the ILO, which has
already found that Britain has breached conventions it signed on good labour
practices nine times since 1979.
The TUC argues that ILO convention 98 - ratified by Britain in 1949 -
upholds the general principle that no person should be prejudiced in
employment by reason of trade union membership or legitimate trade union
activities.
The TUC has already complained to the ILO over two other parts of the Trade
Union Reform and Employment Rights Bill. Those cover the abolition of the
wages councils - ending legal protection for the low-paid - and the removal
of the statutory duty on the conciliation service Acas to promote collective
bargaining.
The TUC is lobbying some Conservative backbenchers in the hope that they may
oppose the amendment, which has concerned some Tory peers. But union leaders
believe the Commons will pass the measure and that it will come into force
later this summer.
</TEXT>
