<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Low wage costs 'fail to draw foreign investment'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S LOW labour costs are not attracting investment by foreign
industrial companies, says a study published today by the Trades Union
Congress.
The TUC points out that the share of foreign-owned companies in UK
manufacturing employment fell during most of the 1980s and by 1989 had
recovered only to its 1981 level of 15 per cent.
It says: 'Foreign direct investment, a measure of financial flows which
includes takeovers, increased between 1985 and 1989 but more than half of
this took the form of takeovers of existing assets rather than new
investment.'
It points out that inward direct investment has fallen sharply from 3.4 per
cent of gross domestic product in 1989 to 1.8 per cent last year.
Since 1985 the net outward investment flow has 'amounted to a loss' of more
than Pounds 36bn at 1992 prices - equivalent to more than a year's
industrial investment in plant and machinery.
The TUC also argues that Britain has lower wage rates than its main
industrialised trading rivals but the country's competitiveness remains weak
because of poor productivity due to the lack of skills and training, and a
low level of technological investment.
According to the TUC's figures for 1991, wages remain lower in Britain than
the US, Germany, France and Italy but productivity remains even lower.
The TUC says that Britain is in no position to compete on labour costs with
low-wage economies such as Hong Kong, South Korea, Taiwan and Singapore but
'nor is it yet in a position to compete with other industrialised countries
on skills, productivity and innovation'.
 ---------------------------------------------------------------
         BRITAIN'S MANUFACTURING UNIT LABOUR COSTS 1991
 ---------------------------------------------------------------
            Labour costs    Productivity    Unit Labour costs
 ---------------------------------------------------------------
UK              100             100              100
US              115             175               66
Japan            98             150               65
German          124             175               71
France          114             139               82
Italy           128             121              106
 ---------------------------------------------------------------
Source: TUC Calculated from US Dept of Labor and OECD
