<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Australian dollar slips as deficit raises fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE AUSTRALIAN dollar yesterday fell to levels last seen during the 'banana
republic' crisis of 1986 as financial markets responded to a
worse-than-expected current account deficit for April.
The government said the deficit contracted to ADollars 1.7bn (Pounds 760m),
from a restated ADollars 1.9bn in March, mainly because of a 7 per cent fall
in the value of imports and a 2 per cent increase in exports.
However, the deficit was significantly higher than market forecasts of
between ADollars 700m and ADollars 1.3bn, contributing to fears that
Australia's sluggish economic recovery may be unsustainable.
The Australian dollar closed 1.5 cents lower at 67.68 US cents in Sydney, in
spite of intervention by the Reserve Bank, and dealers said downward
pressure was likely to resume when markets re-open today.
The currency also fell to fresh lows against the Japanese yen for the fourth
consecutive day, reaching a trough of Y72.44 before closing at Y72.60 from
Y74.10 on Friday.
The Reserve Bank's trade weighted index fell from 50.5 to 49.4, down 13 per
cent since May 1992, and just 0.1 points above the record low of 49.3 in
1986.
The 1986 low followed a warning by Mr Paul Keating, the then federal
treasurer, that Australia was heading for a 'banana republic' debt crisis
unless it solved its chronic current account problems.
Mr Ralph Willis, finance minister, said yesterday the cumulative current
account deficit for the year to the end of June was 'broadly in line' with
the government's budget forecast of ADollars 15bn.
Economists said the April figures were out of line with weak domestic
activity, suggesting that Australia had made little headway in reducing
imports, while the sluggish world economy had slowed export growth.
A further batch of figures due today is expected to confirm that Australian
gross domestic product is growing at about 2.5 per cent a year, in line with
official fore-casts.
Growth of at least 3 per cent a year would be required to achieve the
government's main economic aim of reducing unemployment from the current
level of just under 11 per cent.
However, the bad current account news and the weakness of the currency
suggest that the Reserve Bank will be reluctant to use monetary policy to
encourage faster economic growth.
Fiscal policy is also constrained by market worries about the growing budget
deficit, which is likely to exceed ADollars 16bn in the year to the end of
June, compared to ADollars 12bn in 1991-92.
</TEXT>
