<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / EC finds evidence on market access elusive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE authorities have put off providing the European Commission with
information on the government's recent procurement record despite persistent
requests, a Commission official said yesterday.
The Commission has given Japan a list of 20 product sectors where it would
like to see greater Japanese government procurement from EC companies in the
light of its Y10,700bn (Pounds 64bn) economic stimulus package announced
last summer. The sectors include motor vehicles, telecommunications,
computers, transport equipment and aerospace equipment.
'We don't want to just hear that there has been a new stimulus package, like
a fireworks festival, without knowing what the result is,' a Commission
official said. 'We are asking the Japanese authorities to reveal (that)
information,' the official said. 'Otherwise it becomes void of meaning.'
In January Japan reluctantly agreed to an EC proposal to monitor EC-Japan
trade to analyse the factors affecting the comparative performance of EC
products on the Japanese market. The aim was to conduct a joint analysis of
EC companies' performance in Japanese markets to determine what problems
they faced and what could be done to deal with those problems.
The EC proposal came amid mounting concern about Japan's growing trade
surplus with the EC which increased 14 per cent in 1992 to a record Dollars
31.2bn and was at first hailed as a more rigorous EC approach to trade with
Japan.
Although the Commission has taken pains to stress that the analysis was to
be a co-operative effort, the business of an EC-Japan working group was
hampered from the start by disputes over the proper statistics to use to
monitor trade between the two sides.
At high-level consultations which followed in April, Mr Horst Krenzler,
director-general for external economic relations at the EC Commission, made
clear the EC expects substantial progress in the analysis, including the
effects ot the economic stimulation package on imports, by the time of the
EC-Japan summit in July. An official at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs
responsible for European matters, denied that the failure to provide
information was deliberate. 'We are aware that the EC is interested in such
information but we have not been asked officially to provide information on
specific government purchases,' he said.
</TEXT>
