<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Japan output fall points to frail economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S economy is bumping along the uneven bottom of the downturn which
started about two years ago, according to official figures published
yesterday. These showed that industrial production fell in April, reversing
gains in the previous two months.
Industrial output fell by 2.2 per cent in April from the month before, after
rising in both March and February. Those gains had encouraged some Tokyo
politicans and economists to predict the economy was starting to recover.
The fall in production in April - combined with weak housing starts, which
rose by 1.1 per cent from April last year, and the impact of the
strengthened yen on export industries - suggest the economy remains frail.
However, the Ministry of International Trade and Industry expects industrial
production will start to recover from the autumn, largely because industry
is finally making sustained progress in reducing its inventories of unsold
products,
In spite of the fall in production, inventories of unsold products fell in
April by 1.7 per cent from the month before - to stand 4.9 per cent lower
than April 1992.
It was the fifth consecutive month in which inventories had declined.
Housing starts weakened considerably from March, when they rose by 9.3 per
cent, possibly influenced by the end of the financial year.
April starts on houses by private individuals fell by 2 per cent from the
previous month. Houses being built with loans from the private sector fell
by 11.6 per cent, in part because home buyers expect mortgage rates to rise
following the recent increase in the long-term prime lending rates of the
long-term credit banks.
Meanwhile, the Japan foreign trade council predicted that Japan's
merchandise trade surplus for the year to next April would rise by 17.6 per
cent from the previous year to Dollars 130bn (Pounds 83bn).
Exports would rise by 6.9 per cent to Dollars 368bn, while imports would
increase by only 1.9 per cent to Dollars 237.5bn.
</TEXT>
