<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Illusory gains of Britain's 'competitive devaluation'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FROM the sheltered environment of the British Home Office, chancellor
Kenneth Clarke must step into the real world. Managing the government's
current exchange rate and fiscal policies in the face of the harsh financial
markets and the UK's irritated European partners leaves little room for the
robust approach. Mr Clarke may find it politic to join the rest of his
colleagues in biting his lip when Britain's partners boo and hiss.
The ostensible cause of the present continental hostility towards the UK is
the accumulating evidence that British economic growth has revived,
following sterling's exit from the European exchange rate mechanism last
September. Meanwhile, the rest of northern Europe slips towards recession.
With economic cycles so out of line, the British government argues that
re-entry into the ERM would be foolish. But even if Britain's
Euro-enthusiastic chancellor wanted to bring sterling back into the ERM, it
is uncertain that re-entry would soothe the wounds.
More likely, the UK would be accused of trying to 'lock-in' a lower exchange
rate, at the expense of its European partners. For the UK, along with Spain
and Italy, stands charged with using last September's difficulties to gain
an advantage through 'beggar-thy-neighbour' devaluations. Mr Erik Hoffmeyer,
the Danish central bank chief, said last week that monetary co-operation in
Europe had broken down because devaluing currencies had been allowed to
'win' an unjustified advantage.
Mr Hoffmeyer is not the first person to make this charge. Mr Jean-Luc
Dehaene, Belgium's prime minister, said recently that monetary union was
needed to 'put an end to competitive devaluations.' Mr Jacques Delors, the
European Commission president, also worries that the Single Market would not
survive if Europe were hit by further 'competitive devaluations'.
The UK, Spain and Italy have indeed seen an improvement in the price
competitiveness of their exports within Europe since last summer, as the
charts show. Against a trade-weighted basket of European currencies and
adjusted for relative inflation rates, the Spanish peseta and the Italian
lira have both depreciated by 14 per cent since last August. The UK real
exchange rate initially fell by 13 per cent, but sterling's subsequent
relative strength has reduced the gains in export competitiveness, within
Europe, to 7 per cent.
The accusation of competitive devaluation does not seem fair. The
implication that Spain, Italy or the UK deliberately chose to devalue does
not fit the facts. Politicians in all three countries staked their
credibility on defending the ERM parities; some, notably Mr Norman Lamont,
have suffered for their failure. Since all three countries have suffered
rising trade deficits in recent years, it seems wrong to argue that these
devaluations increased competitive advantage. They were rather about
removing the competitive disadvantage of over-valued real exchange rates.
In the case of the UK, the charge is empirically incorrect. Since the
beginning of 1987, when the hardened ERM emerged, Spanish competitiveness
has improved by 7 per cent, while Italian competitiveness has improved by 11
per cent. But UK competitiveness has declined by 9 per cent, as the chart
shows. The UK's gains since last summer do not compensate for the loss of
competitiveness during sterling's appreciation between 1987 and 1988 and the
UK's relatively high inflation between the end of 1989 and 1992.
The charge that the British government engineered a competitive devaluation
looks weak. The risk for the rest of Europe is not that the UK is going to
'lock-in' at too competitive a rate. The danger for continental Europe is
rather that the combination of Britain's trade and fiscal deficits with a
bombastic chancellor may send sterling spiralling down again, unless
sterling rejoins the ERM soon. A better strategy for northern Europe would
be to stop complaining and start wooing.
