<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Go-ahead from India for ABB's locomotive deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE INDIAN government has approved, after more than five years of argument,
a controversial Dollars 190m contract to import high-technology electric
locomotives from Asea Brown Boveri, the European engineering combine.
The deal has faced intense opposition from supporters of India's large
domestic raliway engineering industry, who argued the country should build
its own locomotives with the minimum of overseas help. Critics also said
that India, a poor country, could not afford state-of-the art technology.
But the cabinet of Mr P V Narasimha Rao, the prime minister, on Friday
approved a contract for the import of 30 locomotives, and for the transfer
of technology which would enable Indian factories to produce many more such
machines over the coming decade.
India first invited bids for the contract in 1987, but it was not until
March 1992 that it decided to grant the contract to ABB, rather than three
other international bidders.
The deal's opponents were helped when the issue went before the Railway
Convention Committee, a government advisory panel, last autumn.
The panel said it would be better for India to develop its own cheaper
techology, adding that ABB's locomotives, powered by a newly-developed
alternating current motor controlled by microchips, would be much more
expensive than an upgraded version of India's existing electric locomotives,
run on traditional direct current motors.
However, the cabinet has accepted ABB's argument that its machines will be
cheaper and easier to run in the long term.
Ministers may also have been swayed by concern that India, now opening its
economy wider to foreigners, should not be seen turning its back on a
foreign company already committed more than most to India. ABB's Indian
affiliate employs more than 4,000.
</TEXT>
