<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Venezuelan 'confusion' attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSEPH MANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CARACAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
VENEZUELA'S leading business association, Fedecamaras, has warned that
delays by the Congress in choosing a new interim president have caused a
power vacuum and a spate of national confusion.
The crisis developed after May 21, when the chairman of the Venezuelan
senate, Senator Octavio Lepage was sworn in as acting president of
Venezuela, in place of President Carlos Andres Perez who was suspended from
office to face corruption charges.
The governing Democratic Action (AD) party and opposition groups have not
yet agreed on a replacement for Mr Lepage to complete Mr Perez's term, which
is to expire next February.
At the weekend, the ruling party suffered a defeat in two gubernatorial
elections. In the eastern state of Sucre, the candidate for the socialist
party MAS, Mr Ramon Martnez, beat the AD contender, Mr Gaston Navarro. In
the western state of Barinas, unofficial returns gave a narrow win to the
candidate of the main opposition Christian democratic Copei party, Mr
Gerhard Cartay, over Mr Rafael Rosales of AD.
The results mean that opposition parties have now wrested control of most
state governorships away from the ruling party. Of the 22 governorships,
Copei holds 11, while AD has eight.
