<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Green group calls for limits on world trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PROPOSALS for a new and powerful world trade body in place of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade should be taken out of the Uruguay Round of
global trade talks and 'greened', the World Wide Fund for Nature says today.
The Swiss-based environmental group has timed its latest shot across Gatt's
bows for the opening of the OECD ministerial meeting in Paris tomorrow, when
trade issues and completion of the Uruguay Round will top the agenda.
WWF says the current proposal for a multilateral trade organisation is not
compatible with the goal of sustainable development set out at the Earth
Summit last year. It says the MTO should recognise 'the need to set limits
on trade in order to adequately protect the environment'.
Arguing that the creation of the MTO has been 'unacceptably secretive', WWF
also wants the MTO draft opened for public consultation rather than decided
by trade negotiators behind closed doors.
Environmental groups, especially in the US, have been campaigning vigorously
against the MTO, which would subsume Gatt and proposed sister bodies on
intellectual property, such as patents and copyright, and trade in services.
They argue that the MTO would institutionalise the primacy of free trade
over environmental protection and make it easier to challenge high national
standards on environmental protection as unfair trade barriers.
These charges are denied by governments taking part in the round but the
campaign has reinforced fears that the MTO proposal could threaten US
Congressional approval of the Uruguay Round package of trade liberalising
measures.
The environmentalists' hand has also been strengthened by the more explicit
environmental protection language in the North American Free Trade Agreement
by the US, Mexico and Canada.
WWF proposals for reforming the MTO include making environmental protection
and eradication of poverty explicit objectives, giving non-governmental
organisations rights of consultation and enabling them to make submissions
to trade disputes investigations, aa well as establishment of a trade and
sustainable development council within the MTO.
</TEXT>
