<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / End of immigrant housing drive may decelerate growth in
Israel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of Israel said yesterday that economic growth could slow down in
the country because of the end of a house building boom, Reuter reports from
Jerusalem.
It also urged the government to accelerate the sale of public companies,
increase competition and reform the labour market.
A government building drive to house an influx of immigrants from the former
Soviet Union had boosted the economy for two years but the fillip was over,
said the central bank said in its 1992 report.
It said gross domestic product rose 6.6 per cent (revised from 6.4 per cent)
in 1992, compared with 6.2 per cent (revised from 5.9 per cent) in 1991.
Exports had displaced housing as the key growth factor, rising 14.4 per cent
in 1992.
But the report said this was, in part, compensation for a decline of 1.5 per
cent in 1991 exports, prompted by the Gulf War when activity was slowed by
Iraqi Scud missile attacks.
Unemployment, which the central bank called the government's main economic
problem, rose to 11.2 per cent in 1992, from 10.6 per cent in 1991.
Inflation was in single digits for the first time in 23 years - 9.4 per cent
compared with 18 per cent in 1991.
'Not enough was done this year in the area of privatisation, increasing
competition and making the labour market more flexible,' the 350-page report
said, echoing charges in January by Mr Haim Stoessel, Tel Aviv Stock
Exchange chairman, that the government had missed an opportunity by not
selling more companies in 1992.
The sale of shares in three state companies raised 1.1bn shekels (Pounds
256m) in a year when the general stock market index rose by nearly 74 per
cent on doubled volume.
'There was room for increasing competition in the communications, public
transport and banking branches. 'In the banking area, (there is a need for
reform) that will increase competition, while reducing potential conflicts
and maintaining banking stability,' the report said.
Mr Yitzhak Rabin, Israeli prime minister, has reshuffled the cabinet to
quell a government crisis which, he said, could have disrupted the Middle
East peace talks.
Mr Rabin, convincing ministers in his Labour party to cede portfolios to the
leftist Meretz bloc on Sunday, ended the crisis that had begun last month
when the ultra-religious Shas party demanded he remove Ms Shulamit Aloni,
outspoken education minister.
</TEXT>
