<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Independent board for S African Broadcasting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT FW de Klerk yesterday announced the appointment of the first
independent board of governors for the state-owned South African
Broadcasting Corporation, for decades the mouthpiece of the ruling National
party.
The new 25-member board, chosen on recommendations by an independent
multi-racial panel of jurists, is to be chaired by Professor Frederick van
Zyl Slabbert, a respected academic and former liberal politician.
The board is charged with ensuring the impartiality of the SABC before the
country's first multi-racial elections, due by April next. Constitutional
negotiators plan to announce an election date on Thursday.
Yesterday, Mr de Klerk met Mr Nelson Mandela, leader of the African National
Congress, to discuss the board appointments before the final announcement.
This underlined increasing co-operation by the government and the ANC on
such issues of state.
The new board includes Mr Christo Viljoen, the outgoing chairman, Prof
Pieter Potgieter, Dutch Reformed Church moderator, Mr Enos Mabuza, a black
businessman, and Ms Brigalia Bam, an official of the ANC-aligned South
African Council of Churches.
They were chosen on recommendations by an independent panel accepted by
political parties across the range. The panel held public hearings to screen
candidates short-listed from 400 nominations.
Controversy arose after the president had rejected the panel's first
recommendations, which included left-wing nominees with a high political
profile, such as Mr Jakes Gerwel, radical rector of the University of the
Western Cape, left-wing journalists Mr Moeletsi Mbeki and Mr Khaba Mkhize,
and Mr Allister Sparks, a former Rand Daily Mail editor.
Mr de Klerk and Mr Mandela also discussed progress at the constitutional
talks, due to end on Thursday with announcement of a package including an
election date and the outline of an interim constitution.
</TEXT>
