<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Russia seeks aid for republics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Russian government is pressing the Group of Seven industrialised
countries to set up a multi-billion dollar fund to assist the non-Russian
former Soviet republics - and has pledged that it will start the fund with
Dollars 1bn (Pounds 600m) from its own scarce foreign resources.
The plan, being debated within the International Monetary Fund and between
senior officials of the G7 states, would be designed to stimulate trade
bwtween these countries and specially between them and Russia - dominant
market and raw materials supplier in the former Soviet Union.
Mr Konstantin Kagalovsky, the executive director for Russia at the IMF, said
in an interview that 'This fund will be designed to stop the total
disintegration of states - like Moldova, Armenia and Georgia - as well as to
stimulate trade between all the former Soviet republics including the Baltic
states. We should act to see to it that there is not a total disintegration,
as in Yugoslavia.'
Mr Kagalovsky said that over the past year, Russia had given hundreds of
millions of roubles in credit to the former Soviet states - the bulk of it
in 'hidden subsidies' which took the form of subsidised energy and other
products sold at prices often fraction of world levels.
This fund, which Mr Kagalovsky said had been approved by Mr Viktor
Chernomyrdin, the Russian prime minister, would be a way of exercising
'conditionality' on the other former USSR states - rewarding their efforts
to co-operate and trade with each other. Mr Kagalovsky said he expected the
issue would be discussed at the G7 simmit in Tokyo in July and it may be
decided there.
The continuing pulling apart of the former Soviet republics is now causing
increasing concern in Moscow as the effects of severance of links between
industrial partners components becomes more serious.
Mr Boris Yeltsin, the Russian president, has urged the greater integration
of the Commonwealth of Independent States which unites all of the former
Soviet republics except the Baltic countries, Georgia and Azerbaijan - but
so far without noticeable effect.
</TEXT>
