<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / OECD ready for rush to discuss growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A YEAR ago, hardly any top-level ministers showed up.
This year, officials organising the two-day annual ministerial meeting of
the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), which
starts tomorrow in Paris, are wondering how to handle the crush of finance,
trade and foreign ministers planning to attend.
The interest in this week's meeting reflects mounting international concern
about weak global growth, rising unemployment and protectionism.
The US delegation is expected to be headed by Mr Lloyd Bentsen, Treasury
secretary, Mr Mickey Kantor, the special trade representative, Ms Laura
Tyson, head of the president's Council of Economic Advisers, Mr Lawrence
Summers, the Treasury undersecretary responsible for international affairs,
and Mr Ron Brown, the commerce secretary.
Following last Friday's disclosure of weak first quarter US economic growth,
European observers fear that the US will renew pressure on its trading
partners for more expansionary economic policies and trade enhancing
measures, while making clear that Washington will not hesitate to retaliate
against what it perceives to be unfair trading practices.
It is an approach that has provoked alarm among America's allies on several
occasions since President Bill Clinton moved into the White House. If
repeated this week, it would set the scene for a difficult meeting.
In the run up to this week's talks, the OECD secretariat has become
increasingly gloomy about slow global growth.
But it feels that as long as most countries are running large budget
deficits there is little scope for any to adopt a more expansionary fiscal
policy.
A possible exception is Japan, but its ministers will say that they
announced a large fiscal expansion programme earlier this year and should be
left to implement it.
On the other hand, European diplomats recognise the pressures that an uneven
and seemingly jobless recovery are putting on the US administration.
Unemployment will feature large in this week's talks. Ministers will be
presented with the interim conclusions of a two-year study commissioned from
the OECD last year into the industrialised world's jobless problem.
It is stronger on analysis than prescription, offering no magic solutions
while drawing some bleak conclusions.
Europe's job creation record appears to be especially poor, with the net
increase in jobs since the early 1970s having been produced entirely by the
civil service. Europe also has a very high level of long-term unemployed,
with about half the region's jobless without work for more than a year.
These facts could trigger a vigorous debate about the barriers to employment
in Europe and especially those which prevent young people taking low-paid
jobs.
While opponents of 'poverty wages' argue that these create and perpetuate
social problems, the OECD itself is sympathetic to the idea of the young
gaining work experience even if the pay is low.
The problems of rising unemployment in the industrialised world will cast a
shadow over discussion of the OECD's area's relations with non-member
countries.
The delegates will have to reconcile their professed belief in free trade
with the fact that non-OECD countries have been gaining markets from the
industrialised world.
The OECD secretariat is also keen for ministers to consider the implications
for member economies of technological change, especially in the related
fields of communications and computers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
