<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 93 / Major seeks to unite Tories in aftermath of reshuffle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BEDROCK Conservative values will be reaffirmed by Mr John Major this week,
as the prime minister seeks to dispel the sour aftermath of last week's
reshuffle and to focus the party on an agenda that will unite it.
Mr Major's efforts to reassert his authority after Mr Norman Lamont's
departure from the Treasury have so far been hampered by public divisions
among Tory MPs about whether there should be tax increases in the November
budget, and whether the reshuffle should have been more extensive.
Officers of the Tory backbench finance committee are to seek an early
meeting with Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, to discuss how he will
approach his task of reining in public borrowing.
The prime minister's speech to the national Conservative women's conference
at the end of this week is seen as an opportunity to restore the party's
fortunes by concentrating on policies such as widening ownership, extending
individual freedoms and lightening the burdens that government imposes on
business.
The need to find an approach that the entire party can support has been
highlighted during the weekend by the sensitivities about how the balance
between left and right in the new cabinet will work in practice.
Senior party managers will spend this week judging how the reshuffle has
been received in the constituencies and take that into account in deciding
when to hold the Christchurch by-election.
Although no decision has been reached, Tory strategists appear since the
reshuffle to have leaned towards mid-July rather than the autumn for the
contest, where the Conservatives are defending a 23,000 majority.
But fresh sniping at Mr Major himself helped to put the government on the
defensive.
Downing Street dismissed as not worth comment the call by Lord Rees-Mogg, a
former editor of The Times, for Mr Major to resign. It also sought to play
down criticism by Lord Lawson, the former chancellor.
Writing in the London Business School's latest international economic
outlook, Lord Lawson said the government made a mistake in joining the
European exchange rate mechanism in October 1990 at a central rate of DM2.95
to the pound without obtaining Bundesbank support. Britain joined the ERM
when Mr Major was chancellor.
He also said the credibility of the ERM and European exchange rate stability
could only be restored if the Maastricht treaty and its plan for a single
European currency were abandoned.
Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, defended Mr Major, highlighting the
prime minister's role in winning the general election for the Conservatives,
and emphasising that the return of sterling into the ERM was 'not on the
agenda'.
Mr Hunt's comments follow his remarks over the weekend about the
desirability of stable exchange rates, and underline the delicate balance
which ministers are keen to strike over economic policy in particular.
As part of that balance, Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, will serve
on the main economic cabinet committees.
Some rightwingers suggest, however, that the combination of Mr Clarke, Mr
Hunt, and Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade secretary, leaves the government's
economic strategy firmly in the hands of the 'interventionists'.
Lib Dems suggest early end to mortgage tax relief, Page 9
Editorial Comment, Page 19
